search.description: preliminary | final | appended | amended | entered-in-error

annotations.shortDefinition: A map from one set of concepts to one or more other concepts
annotations.definition: A statement of relationships from one set of concepts to one or more other concepts - either code systems or data elements, or classes in class models.
A nested type in ConceptMap: Mappings for an individual concept in the source to one or more concepts in the target.

annotation.shortDefinition: Code System (if value set crosses code systems)
annotation.definition: An absolute URI that identifies the Code System (if the source is a value set that crosses more than one code system).
Identity (code or path) or the element/item being mapped.

annotation.shortDefinition: Concept in target system for element
annotation.definition: A concept from the target value set that this concept maps to.
annotation.comment: Ideally there would only be one map, with equal or equivalent mapping. But multiple maps are allowed for several narrower options, or to assert that other concepts are unmatched.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ConceptMap: A set of additional dependencies for this mapping to hold. This mapping is only applicable if the specified element can be resolved, and it has the specified value.

annotation.shortDefinition: Reference to element/field/valueset mapping depends on
annotation.definition: A reference to a specific concept that holds a coded value. This can be an element in a FHIR resource, or a specific reference to a data element in a different specification (e.g. v2) or a general reference to a kind of data field, or a reference to a value set with an appropriately narrow definition.
An absolute URI that identifies the code system of the dependency code (if the source/dependency is a value set that crosses code systems).
Identity (code or path) or the element/item that the map depends on / refers to.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ConceptMap: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of a individual to contact
annotation.definition: The name of an individual to contact regarding the concept map.
annotation.comment: If there is no named individual, the telecom is for the organization as a whole.

annotation.shortDefinition: Contact details for individual or publisher
annotation.definition: Contact details for individual (if a name was provided) or the publisher.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ConceptMap: A concept from the target value set that this concept maps to.

annotation.definition: An absolute URI that identifies the code system of the target code (if the target is a value set that cross code systems).
annotation.comment: Should be a version specific reference.

annotation.shortDefinition: Code that identifies the target element
annotation.definition: Identity (code or path) or the element/item that the map refers to.

annotation.shortDefinition: equivalent | equal | wider | subsumes | narrower | specializes | inexact | unmatched | disjoint
annotation.definition: The equivalence between the source and target concepts (counting for the dependencies and products). The equivalence is read from target to source (e.g. the target is 'wider' than the source).
A description of status/issues in mapping that conveys additional information not represented in the structured data.

annotation.shortDefinition: Other elements required for this mapping (from context)
annotation.definition: A set of additional dependencies for this mapping to hold. This mapping is only applicable if the specified element can be resolved, and it has the specified value.

annotation.shortDefinition: Other concepts that this mapping also produces
annotation.definition: A set of additional outcomes from this mapping to other elements. To properly execute this mapping, the specified element must be mapped to some data element or source that is in context. The mapping may still be useful without a place for the additional data elements, but the equivalence cannot be relied on.

annotation.shortDefinition: Globally unique logical id for concept map
annotation.definition: An absolute URL that is used to identify this concept map when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance. This SHALL be a URL, SHOULD be globally unique, and SHOULD be an address at which this concept map is (or will be) published.

annotation.shortDefinition: Additional identifier for the concept map
annotation.definition: Formal identifier that is used to identify this concept map when it is represented in other formats, or referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance.
annotation.comment: Typically, this is used for values that can go in a v3 II data type.

annotation.shortDefinition: Logical id for this version of the concept map
annotation.definition: The identifier that is used to identify this version of the concept map when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or instance. This is an arbitrary value managed by the profile author manually and the value should be a timestamp.
annotation.comment: There may be multiple resource versions of the concept map that have this same identifier.

annotation.shortDefinition: Informal name for this concept map
annotation.definition: A free text natural language name describing the concept map.
annotation.comment: Not expected to be unique.
annotation.requirements: Support human navigation.

annotation.shortDefinition: Content intends to support these contexts
annotation.definition: The content was developed with a focus and intent of supporting the contexts that are listed. These terms may be used to assist with indexing and searching of concept maps.
annotation.requirements: Assist in searching for appropriate concept maps.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of the publisher (Organization or individual)
annotation.definition: The name of the individual or organization that published the concept map.
annotation.comment: Usually an organization, but may be an individual. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.
annotation.requirements: Helps establish the "authority/credibility" of the concept map. May also allow for contact.

annotation.definition: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.
annotation.comment: May be a web site, an email address, a telephone number (tel:), etc.

annotation.shortDefinition: Human language description of the concept map
annotation.definition: A free text natural language description of the use of the concept map - reason for definition, conditions of use, etc.
annotation.comment: The description is not intended to describe the semantics of the concept map. The description should capture its intended use, which is needed for ensuring integrity for its use in models across future changes.
annotation.requirements: Human understandability.

annotation.definition: Explains why this concept map is needed and why it's been constrained as it has.
annotation.comment: This element does not describe the usage of the concept map (that's done in comments), rather it's for traceability of *why* the element is either needed or why the constraints exist as they do. This may be used to point to source materials or specifications that drove the structure of this data element.

annotation.definition: A copyright statement relating to the concept map and/or its contents.
annotation.comment: Frequently, the copyright differs between the concept map, and codes that are included. The copyright statement should clearly differentiate between these when required.

annotation.definition: The status of the concept map.
annotation.comment: Allows filtering of ConceptMaps that are appropriate for use.
annotation.requirements: Identify when/if the concept map should be used.

annotation.shortDefinition: If for testing purposes, not real usage
annotation.definition: This ConceptMap was authored for testing purposes (or education/evaluation/marketing), and is not intended to be used for genuine usage.
annotation.comment: Allows filtering of ConceptMaps that are appropriate for use.

annotation.definition: The date that the concept map status was last changed.
annotation.comment: Note that this is not the same as the resource last-modified-date, since the resource may be a secondary representation of the concept map.
annotation.requirements: Need to know when a concept map was first legal for use or became withdrawn or replaced.

annotation.shortDefinition: Identifies the source of the concepts which are being mapped
annotation.definition: The source value set that specifies the concepts that are being mapped.
annotation.comment: Should be a version specific reference. URIs SHOULD be absolute.

annotation.definition: The target value set provides context to the mappings. Note that the mapping is made between concepts, not between value sets, but the value set provides important context about how the concept mapping choices are made.
annotation.comment: Should be a version specific reference. URIs SHOULD be absolute.

annotation.shortDefinition: Mappings for a concept from the source set
annotation.definition: Mappings for an individual concept in the source to one or more concepts in the target.
annotation.comment: Generally, the ideal is that there would only be one mapping for each concept in the source value set, but a given concept may be mapped mutliple times with different comments or dependencies.

search.description: The concept map publication date

search.description: Additional identifier for the concept map

search.description: Reference to element/field/valueset mapping depends on

search.description: Reference to element/field/valueset mapping depends on

search.description: Text search in the description of the concept map

search.description: The url of the concept map

search.description: Provides context to the mappings

search.name: sourcecode
search.description: Identifies element being mapped

search.description: Name of the concept map

search.name: context
search.description: A use context assigned to the concept map

search.name: publisher
search.description: Name of the publisher of the concept map

search.name: targetcode
search.description: Code that identifies the target element

search.name: status
search.description: Status of the concept map

annotations.shortDefinition: Detailed information about conditions, problems or diagnoses
annotations.definition: Use to record detailed information about conditions, problems or diagnoses recognized by a clinician. There are many uses including: recording a Diagnosis during an Encounter; populating a problem List or a Summary Statement, such as a Discharge Summary.
annotations.todo: * Age is questionable, you might well need a range of Age or even (in practice) a text like "in their teens". => new ballot comment. * Todo: discuss the applicability of assessing stages * Change the description: it is circular.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Condition: The anatomical location where this condition manifests itself.

annotation.definition: Code that identifies the structural location.
annotation.comment: May include laterality.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Condition: Supporting Evidence / manifestations that are the basis on which this condition is suspected or confirmed.

annotation.definition: A manifestation or symptom that led to the recording of this condition.
Links to other relevant information, including pathology reports.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Condition: Further conditions, problems, diagnoses, procedures or events or the substance that caused/triggered this Condition.

annotation.shortDefinition: Relationship target by means of a predefined code
annotation.definition: Code that identifies the target of this relationship. The code takes the place of a detailed instance target.
Target of the relationship.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Condition: Clinical stage or grade of a condition. May include formal severity assessments.

annotation.definition: A simple summary of the stage such as "Stage 3". The determination of the stage is disease-specific.
Reference to a formal record of the evidence on which the staging assessment is based.
annotation.todo: When an assessment resource / framework is developed, this will be changed from Any to something narrower.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Condition: Further conditions, problems, diagnoses, procedures or events or the substance that preceded this Condition.

annotation.shortDefinition: Relationship target by means of a predefined code
annotation.definition: Code that identifies the target of this relationship. The code takes the place of a detailed instance target.
Target of the relationship.

binding.name: ConditionPredecessor
binding.definition: Codes that describe activities or observations that occurred prior to the condition

binding.name: ConditionCause
binding.definition: Codes that describe causes of patient conditions. E.g. Surgical mishap, escalation of a previous condition, etc.

binding.name: ConditionKind
binding.definition: Identification of the Condition or diagnosis.

binding.name: ConditionClinicalStatus
binding.definition: The clinical status of the Condition or diagnosis

code.definition: This is a tentative diagnosis - still a candidate that is under consideration
The patient is being treated on the basis that this is the condition, but it is still not confirmed
There is sufficient diagnostic and/or clinical evidence to treat this as a confirmed condition
This condition has been ruled out by diagnostic and clinical evidence
The statement was entered in error and Is not valid
The condition status is unknown. Note that "unknown" is a value of last resort and every attempt should be made to provide a meaningful value other than "unknown"

binding.name: ConditionSeverity
binding.definition: A subjective assessment of the severity of the condition as evaluated by the clinician.

binding.name: ManifestationOrSymptom
binding.definition: Codes that describe the manifestation or symptoms of a condition.

binding.name: ConditionCategory
binding.definition: A category assigned to the condition. E.g. finding | Condition | diagnosis | concern | condition

code.definition: The patient considers the condition an issue to be addressed
A symptom of a condition (as might be mentioned in a review of systems)
An observation made by a healthcare provider
This is a judgment made by a healthcare provider that the patient has a particular disease or condition

binding.name: BodySite
binding.definition: Codes describing anatomical locations. May include laterality

annotation.definition: This records identifiers associated with this condition that are defined by business processed and/ or used to refer to it when a direct URL reference to the resource itself is not appropriate (e.g. in CDA documents, or in written / printed documentation).
annotation.requirements: Need to allow connection to a wider workflow.

annotation.definition: Indicates the patient who the condition record is associated with.
Encounter during which the condition was first asserted.
Person who takes responsibility for asserting the existence of the condition as part of the electronic record.
Estimated or actual date the condition/problem/diagnosis was first detected/suspected.

annotation.shortDefinition: Identification of the condition, problem or diagnosis
annotation.definition: Identification of the condition, problem or diagnosis.
A category assigned to the condition. E.g. complaint | symptom | finding | diagnosis.
annotation.comment: The categorization is often highly contextual and may appear poorly differentiated or not very useful in other contexts.
annotation.v2Mapping: 'problem' if from PRB-3. 'diagnosis' if from DG1 segment in PV1 message

annotation.shortDefinition: provisional | working | confirmed | refuted | entered-in-error | unknown
annotation.definition: The clinical status of the condition.
annotation.rimMapping: .code (pre or post-coordinated in) Can use valueNegationInd for refuted

annotation.definition: A subjective assessment of the severity of the condition as evaluated by the clinician.
annotation.comment: Coding of the severity with a terminology is preferred, where possible.
annotation.rimMapping: Can be pre/post-coordinated into value. Or ./inboundRelationship[typeCode=SUBJ].source[classCode=OBS, moodCode=EVN, code="severity"].value

annotation.shortDefinition: Estimated or actual date, date-time, or age
annotation.definition: Estimated or actual date or date-time the condition began, in the opinion of the clinician.
annotation.comment: Age is generally used when the patient reports an age at which the Condition began to occur.

annotation.definition: The date or estimated date that the condition resolved or went into remission. This is called "abatement" because of the many overloaded connotations associated with "remission" or "resolution" - Conditions are never really resolved, but they can abate.
annotation.comment: There is no explicit distinction between resolution and remission because in many cases the distinction is not clear. Age is generally used when the patient reports an age at which the Condition abated. If there is no abatement element, it is unknown whether the condition has resolved or entered remission; applications and users should generally assume that the condition is still valid.
annotation.rimMapping: .effectiveTime.high or .inboundRelationship[typeCode=SUBJ].source[classCode=OBS, moodCode=EVN, code="age at remission"].value or .inboundRelationship[typeCode=SUBJ]source[classCode=CONC, moodCode=EVN].status=completed

annotation.definition: Clinical stage or grade of a condition. May include formal severity assessments.
Supporting Evidence / manifestations that are the basis on which this condition is suspected or confirmed.
annotation.comment: The evidence may be a simple list of coded symptoms/manifestations, or references to observations or formal assessments, or both.

annotation.definition: The anatomical location where this condition manifests itself.
annotation.comment: May be a summary code, or a reference to a very precise definition of the location, or both.

annotation.definition: Further conditions, problems, diagnoses, procedures or events or the substance that caused/triggered this Condition.
annotation.comment: Although a condition may be caused by a substance, this is not intended to be used to record allergies/adverse reactions to substances.

annotation.definition: Further conditions, problems, diagnoses, procedures or events or the substance that preceded this Condition.
Additional information about the Condition. This is a general notes/comments entry for description of the Condition, its diagnosis and prognosis.

annotations.shortDefinition: A conformance statement
annotations.definition: A conformance statement is a set of requirements for a desired implementation or a description of how a target application fulfills those requirements in a particular implementation.
A nested type in Conformance: Definition of an operation or a named query and with its parameters and their meaning and type.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name by which the operation/query is invoked
annotation.definition: The name of a query, which is used in the _query parameter when the query is called.
annotation.comment: The name here SHOULD be the same as the name in the definition, unless there is a name clash and the name cannot be used.

annotation.definition: Where the formal definition can be found.
annotation.comment: This can be used to build ah HTML form to invoke the operation, for instance.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: Software that is covered by this conformance statement. It is used when the conformance statement describes the capabilities of a particular software version, independent of an installation.

annotation.shortDefinition: A name the software is known by
annotation.definition: Name software is known by.
The version identifier for the software covered by this statement.
annotation.comment: If possible, version should be specified, as statements are likely to be different for different versions of software.

annotation.definition: Date this version of the software released.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: Information about security implementation from an interface perspective - what a client needs to know.

annotation.definition: Server adds CORS headers when responding to requests - this enables javascript applications to use the server.
annotation.comment: The easiest CORS headers to add are Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * & Access-Control-Request-Method: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE. All servers SHOULD support CORS.

annotation.shortDefinition: OAuth | SMART-on-FHIR | NTLM | Basic | Kerberos | Certificates
annotation.definition: Types of security services are supported/required by the system.

annotation.shortDefinition: General description of how security works
annotation.definition: General description of how security works.
Certificates associated with security profiles.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of a individual to contact
annotation.definition: The name of an individual to contact regarding the conformance.
annotation.comment: If there is no named individual, the telecom is for the organization as a whole.

annotation.shortDefinition: Contact details for individual or publisher
annotation.definition: Contact details for individual (if a name was provided) or the publisher.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: A document definition.

annotation.definition: Mode of this document declaration - whether application is producer or consumer.
A description of how the application supports or uses the specified document profile. For example, when are documents created, what action is taken with consumed documents, etc.

annotation.shortDefinition: Constraint on a resource used in the document
annotation.definition: A constraint on a resource used in the document.
annotation.comment: The first resource is the document resource.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: Search parameters for implementations to support and/or make use of - either references to ones defined in the specification, or additional ones defined for/by the implementation.

annotation.definition: The name of the search parameter used in the interface.
annotation.comment: Parameter names cannot overlap with standard parameter names, and standard parameters cannot be redefined.

annotation.definition: An absolute URI that is a formal reference to where this parameter was first defined, so that a client can be confident of the meaning of the search parameter (a reference to [[[SearchParameter.url]]]).
annotation.comment: This SHOULD be present, and matches SearchParameter.url.

annotation.shortDefinition: number | date | string | token | reference | composite | quantity | uri
annotation.definition: The type of value a search parameter refers to, and how the content is interpreted.
annotation.comment: While this can be looked up from the definition, it is included here as a convenience for systems that auto-generate a query interface based on the server conformance statement. It SHALL be the same as the type in the search parameter definition.

annotation.definition: This allows documentation of any distinct behaviors about how the search parameter is used. For example, text matching algorithms.

annotation.shortDefinition: Types of resource (if a resource reference)
annotation.definition: Types of resource (if a resource is referenced).
annotation.comment: This SHALL be the same as or a proper subset of the resources listed in the search parameter definition.

annotation.shortDefinition: missing | exact | contains | not | text | in | not-in | below | above | type
annotation.definition: A modifier supported for the search parameter.
Chained names supported.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: A description of the messaging capabilities of the solution.

annotation.definition: An address to which messages and/or replies are to be sent.
annotation.comment: For solutions that do not use network addresses for routing, it can be just an identifier.

annotation.definition: Length if the receiver's reliable messaging cache in minutes (if a receiver) or how long the cache length on the receiver should be (if a sender).
annotation.comment: If this value is missing then the application does not implement (receiver) or depend on (sender) reliable messaging.

annotation.definition: Documentation about the system's messaging capabilities for this endpoint not otherwise documented by the conformance statement. For example, process for becoming an authorized messaging exchange partner.
A description of the solution's support for an event at this end point.
annotation.comment: The same event may be listed up to two times - once as sender and once as receiver.
annotation.todo: Need to add follow-ups and need to do more to flesh out messaging dynamic model.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: Identifies a specific implementation instance that is described by the conformance statement - i.e. a particular installation, rather than the capabilities of a software program.

annotation.definition: Information about the specific installation that this conformance statement relates to.
An absolute base URL for the implementation. This forms the base for REST interfaces as well as the mailbox and document interfaces.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: Identifies a restful operation supported by the solution.

annotation.shortDefinition: read | vread | update | delete | history-instance | validate | history-type | create | search-type
annotation.definition: Coded identifier of the operation, supported by the system resource.

Guidance specific to the implementation of this operation, such as 'delete is a logical delete' or 'updates are only allowed with version id' or 'creates permitted from pre-authorized certificates only'.
annotation.requirements: REST allows a degree of variability in the implementation of RESTful solutions that is useful for exchange partners to be aware of.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Conformance: A specification of the restful capabilities of the solution for a specific resource type.

annotation.shortDefinition: A resource type that is supported
annotation.definition: A type of resource exposed via the restful interface.

annotation.shortDefinition: If update can commit to a new identity
annotation.definition: A flag to indicate that the server allows or needs to allow the client to create new identities on the server (e.g. that is, the client PUTs to a location where there is no existing resource). Allowing this operation means that the server allows the client to create new identities on the server.
annotation.comment: Allowing the clients to create new identities on the server means that the system administrator needs to have confidence that the clients do not create clashing identities between them. Obviously, if there is only one client, this won't happen. While creating identities on the client means that the clients need to be managed, it's much more convenient for many scenarios if such management can be put in place.

annotation.shortDefinition: Logical uri to reference this statement
annotation.definition: An absolute URL that is used to identify this conformance statement when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance. This SHALL be a URL, SHOULD be globally unique, and SHOULD be an address at which this conformance statement is (or will be) published.

annotation.shortDefinition: Logical id for this version of the statement
annotation.definition: The identifier that is used to identify this version of the conformance statement when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or instance. This is an arbitrary value managed by the profile author manually and the value should be a timestamp.
annotation.comment: There may be multiple different instances of a conformance statement that have the same identifier but different versions.

annotation.shortDefinition: Informal name for this conformance statement
annotation.definition: A free text natural language name identifying the conformance statement.
annotation.comment: The name is not expected to be globally unique.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of the publisher (Organization or individual)
annotation.definition: The name of the individual or organization that published the conformance.
annotation.comment: Usually an organization, but may be an individual. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.
annotation.requirements: Helps establish the "authority/credibility" of the conformance. May also allow for contact.

annotation.definition: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.
annotation.comment: May be a web site, an email address, a telephone number (tel:), etc.

annotation.shortDefinition: Human description of the conformance statement
annotation.definition: A free text natural language description of the conformance statement and its use. Typically, this is used when the conformance statement describes a desired rather than an actual solution, for example as a formal expression of requirements as part of an RFP.
annotation.comment: This field cmay include the purpose of this conformance statement, comments about its context etc. This does not need to be populated if the description is adequately implied by the software or implementation details.

annotation.definition: Explains why this conformance statement is needed and why it's been constrained as it has.
annotation.comment: This element does not describe the usage of the conformance statement (that's done in comments), rather it's for traceability of *why* the element is either needed or why the constraints exist as they do. This may be used to point to source materials or specifications that drove the structure of this data element.

annotation.definition: A copyright statement relating to the conformamce statement and/or its contents. Copyright statements are generally legal restrictions on the use and publishing of the details of the system described by the conformance statement.
The status of this conformance statement.
annotation.comment: This is not intended for use with actual conformance statements, but where conformance statements are used to describe possible or desired systems.

annotation.shortDefinition: If for testing purposes, not real usage
annotation.definition: A flag to indicate that this conformance statement is authored for testing purposes (or education/evaluation/marketing), and is not intended to be used for genuine usage.
annotation.comment: Allows filtering of conformance statements that are appropriate for use vs. not.

annotation.definition: The date (and optionally time) when the conformance statement was published.

annotation.shortDefinition: Software that is covered by this conformance statement
annotation.definition: Software that is covered by this conformance statement. It is used when the conformance statement describes the capabilities of a particular software version, independent of an installation.

annotation.shortDefinition: If this describes a specific instance
annotation.definition: Identifies a specific implementation instance that is described by the conformance statement - i.e. a particular installation, rather than the capabilities of a software program.
The version of the FHIR specification on which this conformance statement is based.

annotation.shortDefinition: True if application accepts unknown elements
annotation.definition: A flag that indicates whether the application accepts unknown elements as part of a resource.
annotation.comment: This is not about extensions, but about unknown elements in a resource - these can only arise as later versions of the specification are published, because this is the only place where such elements can be defined. Hence this element is about inter-version compatibility.

annotation.definition: A list of the formats supported by this implementation using their content types.
annotation.comment: "xml" or "json" are allowed, which describe the simple encodings described in the specification (and imply appropriate bundle support). Otherwise, mime types are legal here.

annotation.definition: A list of profiles supported by the system. For a server, "supported by the system" means the system hosts/produces a set of resources, conformant to a particular profile, and allows its clients to search using this profile and to find appropriate data. For a client, it means the system will search by this profile and process data according to the guidance implicit in the profile. See further discussion in [Using Profiles]{profiling.html#profile-uses}.
annotation.comment: Supported profiles are different to the profiles that apply to a particular resource in rest.resource.profile. The resource profile is a general statement of what features of the resource are supported overall by the system - the sum total of the facilities it supports. A supported profile is a deeper statement about the functionality of the data and services provided by the server (or used by the client). A typical case is a laboratory system that produces a set of different reports- this is the list of types of data that it publishes. A key aspect of declaring profiles here is the question of how the client converts knowledge that the server publishes this data into working with the data; the client can inspect individual resources to determine whether they conform to a particular profile, but how does it find the ones that does? It does so by searching using the _profile parameter, so any resources listed here must be valid values for the _profile resource (using the identifier in the target profile). Typical supported profiles cross resource types to describe a network of related resources, so they are listed here rather than by resource. However they do not need to describe more than one resource.

annotation.shortDefinition: If the endpoint is a RESTful one
annotation.definition: A definition of the restful capabilities of the solution, if any.
annotation.comment: Multiple repetitions allow definition of both client and / or server behaviors or possibly behaviors under different configuration settings (for software or requirements statements).

annotation.definition: A description of the messaging capabilities of the solution.
annotation.comment: Multiple repetitions allow the documentation of multiple endpoints per solution.

annotation.definition: A document definition.

code.definition: the signature of the primary or sole author of a health information document. There can be only one primary author of a health information document.
the signature of a health information document coauthor. There can be multiple coauthors of a health information document.

the signature of an individual who is a participant in the health information document but is not an author or coauthor. (Example a surgeon who is required by institutional, regulatory, or legal rules to sign an operative report, but who was not involved in the authorship of that report.)
the signature of an individual who has transcribed a dictated document or recorded written text into a digital machine readable format.

a signature verifying the information contained in a document. (Example a physician is required to countersign a verbal order that has previously been recorded in the medical record by a registered nurse who has carried out the verbal order.)

a signature validating a health information document for inclusion in the patient record. (Example a medical student or resident is credentialed to perform history or physical examinations and to write progress notes. The attending physician signs the history and physical examination to validate the entry for inclusion in the patient's medical record.)
the signature of an individual consenting to what is described in a health information document.
the signature of a witness to any other signature.
the signature of a witness to an event. (Example the witness has observed a procedure and is attesting to this fact.)
the signature of an individual who has witnessed another individual who is known to them signing a document. (Example the identity witness is a notary public.)
the signature of an individual who has witnessed the health care provider counselling a patient.
the signature of an individual who has translated health care information during an event or the obtaining of consent to a treatment.

the signature of a person, device, or algorithm that has reviewed or filtered data for inclusion into the patient record. ( Examples: (1) a medical records clerk who scans a document for inclusion in the medical record, enters header information, or catalogues and classifies the data, or a combination thereof; (2) a gateway that receives data from another computer system and interprets that data or changes its format, or both, before entering it into the patient record.)

the signature of an automated data source. (Examples: (1) the signature for an image that is generated by a device for inclusion in the patient record; (2) the signature for an ECG derived by an ECG system for inclusion in the patient record; (3) the data from a biomedical monitoring device or system that is for inclusion in the patient record.)

the signature on a new amended document of an individual who has corrected, edited, or amended an original health information document. An addendum signature can either be a signature type or a signature sub-type (see 8.1). Any document with an addendum signature shall have a companion document that is the original document with its original, unaltered content, and original signatures. The original document shall be referenced via an attribute in the new document, which contains, for example, the digest of the old document. Whether the original, unaltered, document is always displayed with the addended document is a local matter, but the original, unaltered, document must remain as part of the patient record and be retrievable on demand.

the signature on an original document of an individual who has generated a new amended document. This (original) document shall reference the new document via an additional signature purpose. This is the inverse of an addendum signature and provides a pointer from the original to the amended document.

the signature of an individual who is certifying that the document is invalidated by an error(s), or is placed in the wrong chart. An administrative (error/edit) signature must include an addendum to the document and therefore shall have an addendum signature sub-type (see 8.1). This signature is reserved for the highest health information system administrative classification, since it is a statement that the entire document is invalidated by the error and that the document should no longer be used for patient care, although for legal reasons the document must remain part of the permanent patient record.

annotation.comment: The specification is described once, with general comments, and then specific mappings are made that reference this declaration.

annotation.definition: An absolute URI that identifies the specification that this mapping is expressed to.
annotation.comment: A formal identity for the specification being mapped to helps with identifying maps consistently.

annotation.definition: A name for the specification that is being mapped to.

annotation.definition: Contact details for individual (if a name was provided) or the publisher.

binding.name: UseContext
binding.definition: Indicates the countries, regions, disciplines and other aspects of use this artifact is targeted for use within

binding.name: DataElementSpecificity
binding.definition: Indicates the degree of precision of the data element definition

code.definition: The data element is sufficiently well-constrained that multiple pieces of data captured according to the constraints of the data element will be comparable (though in some cases, a degree of automated conversion/normalization may be required).
The data element is fully specified down to a single value set, single unit of measure, single data type, etc. Multiple pieces of data associated with this data element are fully compareable
The data element allows multiple units of measure having equivalent meaning. E.g. "cc" (cubic centimeter) and "mL".

The data element allows multiple units of measure that are convertable between each other (e.g. Inches and centimeters) and/or allows data to be captured in multiple value sets for which a known mapping exists allowing conversion of meaning
A convertable data element where unit conversions are different only by a power of 10. E.g. g, mg, kg
The data element is unconstrained in units, choice of data types and/or choice of vocabulary such that automated comparison of data captured using the data element is not possible.

annotation.shortDefinition: Globally unique logical id for data element
annotation.definition: An absolute URL that is used to identify this data element when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance. This SHALL be a URL, SHOULD be globally unique, and SHOULD be an address at which this data element is (or will be) published.

annotation.shortDefinition: Logical id to reference this data element
annotation.definition: Formal identifier that is used to identify this data element when it is represented in other formats, or referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance.
annotation.comment: Typically, this is used for values that can go in a v3 II data type.

annotation.shortDefinition: Logical id for this version of the data element
annotation.definition: The identifier that is used to identify this version of the data element when it is referenced in a StructureDefinition, Questionnaire or instance. This is an arbitrary value managed by the definition author manually.
annotation.requirements: There may be multiple resource versions of the data element that have this same identifier. The resource version id will change for technical reasons, whereas the stated version number needs to be under the author's control.

annotation.shortDefinition: Descriptive label for this element definition
annotation.definition: The term used by humans to refer to the data element. Should ideally be unique within the context in which the data element is expected to be used.
annotation.comment: This may be similar to the question used to prompt someone for a data element value, but the purpose is communicating about the data element, not asking the question. (Refer to the 'question' element for the latter.).

annotation.shortDefinition: Content intends to support these contexts
annotation.definition: The content was developed with a focus and intent of supporting the contexts that are listed. These terms may be used to assist with indexing and searching of data element definitions.

annotation.shortDefinition: If for testing purposes, not real usage
annotation.definition: A flag to indicate that this search data elemnt definition is authored for testing purposes (or education/evaluation/marketing), and is not intended to be used for genuine usage.
annotation.comment: Allows filtering of search data element definitions that are appropriate for use vs. not.

annotation.definition: The status of the data element.
annotation.requirements: Allows filtering of data elements that are appropriate for use vs. not.

annotation.shortDefinition: Date for this version of the data element
annotation.definition: The date that the status for this business version of the data element became effective. (I.e. Date the draft was created, date element became active or date element became retired).
annotation.comment: This refers to the "business" version - the DataElement.version which changes based on business processes. It does not refer to the date of the RESTful version which is part of the resource metadata.

annotation.definition: A copyright statement relating to the definition of the data element. Copyright statements are generally legal restrictions on the use and publishing of the details of the definition of the data element.
annotation.comment: The copyright statement does not apply to values for the data element, only to its definition.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of the publisher (Organization or individual)
annotation.definition: The name of the individual or organization that published the data element.
annotation.comment: Usually an organization, but may be an individual. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.
annotation.requirements: Helps establish the "authority/credibility" of the data element. May also allow for contact.

annotation.definition: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.
annotation.comment: May be a web site, an email address, a telephone number (tel:), etc.

annotation.shortDefinition: comparable | fully-specified | equivalent | convertable | scaleable | flexible
annotation.definition: Identifies how precise the data element is in its definition.
annotation.requirements: Allows determining whether the degree of comparability of data element instances - less granular data elements result in data that is less comparable (or at least requires more work to compare).
annotation.todo: Should this be an extension?

annotation.definition: Identifies a specification (other than a terminology) that the elements that make up the DataElement hav some correspondance with.
Defines the structure, type, allowed values and other constraining characteristics of the data element.
annotation.comment: For simple data types there will only be one repetition. For complex data types, multiple repetitions will be present defining a nested structure using the "path" element.

annotations.shortDefinition: An instance of a manufactured thing that is used in the provision of healthcare
annotations.definition: This resource identifies an instance of a manufactured thing that is used in the provision of healthcare without being substantially changed through that activity. The device may be a medical or non-medical device. Medical devices includes durable (reusable) medical equipment, implantable devices, as well as disposable equipment used for diagnostic, treatment, and research for healthcare and public health. Non medical devices may includes things such as a machine, a cellphone, a computer, an application, etc.
annotations.requirements: Allows institutions to track their devices.

annotation.shortDefinition: Instance id from manufacturer, owner, and others

annotation.comment: Often fixed to the device as a barcode and may include names given to the device in local usage. Note that some of the barcodes affixed to the device identify its type, not its instance. For the FDA Mandated Unique Device Identifier (UDI) use the Device.udi element.

annotation.shortDefinition: What kind of device this is

annotation.comment: For the FDA Mandated Unique Device Identifier (UDI) use the Device.udi element.

annotation.definition: The "model" - an identifier assigned by the manufacturer to identify the product by its type. This number is shared by the all devices sold as the same type.
The version of the device, if the device has multiple releases under the same model, or if the device is software or carries firmware.
The Date and time when the device was manufactured.

annotation.shortDefinition: Date and time of expiry of this device (if applicable)
annotation.definition: The date and time beyond which this device is no longer valid or should not be used (if applicable).

United States Food and Drug Administration mandated Unique Device Identifier (UDI). Use the human readable information (the content that the user sees, which is sometimes different to the exact syntax represented in the barcode) - see http://www.fda.gov/MedicalDevices/DeviceRegulationandGuidance/UniqueDeviceIdentification/default.htm.
annotation.comment: The unique identifier may identify an instance of a device uniquely, or it may just identify the type of the device. A portion of the UDI - the DI part - can be extracted from the UDI when required, and used to look up information about the device through the GUDID.

This reference can be used by a client application to distinguish DeviceMetrics that have the same type, but should be interpreted based on their containment location.
Indicates current operational state of the device. For example: On, Off, Standby, etc.

annotation.shortDefinition: black | red | green | yellow | blue | magenta | cyan | white
annotation.definition: Describes the color representation for the metric. This is often used to aid clinicians to track and identify parameter types by color. In practice, consider a Patient Monitor that has ECG/HR and Pleth for example; the parameters are displayed in different characteristic colors, such as HR-blue, BP-green, and PR and SpO2- magenta.
Indicates the category of the observation generation process. A DeviceMetric can be for example a setting, measurement, or calculation.

Describes the measurement repetition time. This is not necessarily the same as the update period. The measurement repetition time can range from milliseconds up to hours. An example for a measurement repetition time in the range of milliseconds is the sampling rate of an ECG. An example for a measurement repetition time in the range of hours is a NIBP that is triggered automatically every hour. The update period may be different than the measurement repetition time, if the device does not update the published observed value with the same frequency as it was measured.

annotation.shortDefinition: Who and/or what test is about
annotation.definition: Who or what the investigation is to be performed on. This is usually a human patient, but diagnostic tests can also be requested on animals, groups of humans or animals, devices such as dialysis machines, or even locations (typically for environmental scans).
The practitioner that holds legal responsibility for ordering the investigation.
Identifiers assigned to this order by the orderer and/or the receiver and/or order fulfiller.
annotation.comment: The identifier.type element is used to distinguish between the identifiers assigned by the orderer (known as the 'Placer' in HL7 v2 ) and the producer of the observations in response to the order ( known the 'Filler' in HL7 v2) . Use the type code "PLAC" for the Placer Identifier and use the type code "FILL" for the Filler identifier.
annotation.todo: finalize type codes.

annotation.shortDefinition: The encounter that this diagnostic order is associated with
annotation.definition: An encounter that provides additional information about the healthcare context in which this request is made.
An explanation or justification for why this diagnostic investigation is being requested.
annotation.comment: This may be used to decide how the diagnostic investigation will be performed, or even if it will be performed at all.

annotation.definition: Additional clinical information about the patient or specimen that may influence test interpretations.
annotation.comment: This information includes diagnosis, clinical findings and other observations. Examples include reporting the amount of inspired carbon dioxide for blood gasses, the point in the menstrual cycle for cervical pap tests, and other conditions that influence test interpretations.

annotation.shortDefinition: If the whole order relates to specific specimens
annotation.definition: One or more specimens that the diagnostic investigation is about.
annotation.comment: Many investigation requests will create a need for specimens, but the request itself is not actually about the specimens. This is provided for when the diagnostic investigation is requested on already existing specimens.

annotation.shortDefinition: proposed | draft | planned | requested | received | accepted | in-progress | review | completed | cancelled | suspended | rejected | failed
annotation.definition: The status of the order.
annotation.comment: Typically the system placing the order sets the status to requested. Thereafter, the order is maintained by the receiver that updates the status as the request is handled.
annotation.rimMapping: .statusCode also influenced by whether a ControlAct fulfillment requeste exists, whether a promise exists, status of the review component, whether a fulfilling observation exists, whether a refusal exists

annotation.definition: The clinical priority associated with this order.
annotation.comment: The Order resource also has a priority. Generally, these should be the same, but they can be different, for instance in the case where the clinician indicates that the order is urgent, but the subsequent workflow process overrule this priority for some reason. The effective default value is "normal".

annotation.shortDefinition: A list of events of interest in the lifecycle
annotation.definition: A summary of the events of interest that have occurred as the request is processed. E.g. when the order was made, various processing steps (specimens received), when it was completed.
annotation.comment: This is not the same as an audit trail - it is a view of the important things that happened in the past. Typically, there would only be one entry for any given status, and systems may not record all the status events.

annotation.definition: The specific diagnostic investigations that are requested as part of this request. Sometimes, there can only be one item per request, but in most contexts, more than one investigation can be requested.
annotation.comment: There would always be at least one item in normal usage, but this is optional so that a workflow can quote order details without having to list the items.

annotations.shortDefinition: A Diagnostic report - a combination of request information, atomic results, images, interpretation, as well as formatted reports
annotations.definition: The findings and interpretation of diagnostic tests performed on patients, groups of patients, devices, and locations, and/or specimens derived from these. The report includes clinical context such as requesting and provider information, and some mix of atomic results, images, textual and coded interpretation, and formatted representation of diagnostic reports.
annotations.comment: This is intended to capture a single report, and is not suitable for use in displaying summary information that covers multiple reports. For example, this resource has not been designed for laboratory cumulative reporting formats nor detailed structured reports for sequencing.
annotations.requirements: To support reporting for any diagnostic report into a clinical data repository.
annotations.committeeNotes: It's not clear how to handle cumulative reports.

annotations.definition: A nested type in DiagnosticReport: A list of key images associated with this report. The images are generally created during the diagnostic process, and may be directly of the patient, or of treated specimens (i.e. slides of interest).

annotation.definition: A comment about the image. Typically, this is used to provide an explanation for why the image is included, or to draw the viewer's attention to important features.
annotation.comment: The comment should be displayed with the image. It would be common for the report to include additional discussion of the image contents in other sections such as the conclusion.
annotation.requirements: The provider of the report should make a comment about each image included in the report.

annotation.definition: Reference to the image source.

binding.definition: Codes that describe Diagnostic Reports

binding.definition: Codes for diagnostic service sections

binding.name: DiagnosticReportStatus
binding.definition: The status of the diagnostic report as a whole

code.definition: The existence of the report is registered, but there is nothing yet available
This is a partial (e.g. initial, interim or preliminary) report: data in the report may be incomplete or unverified
The report is complete and verified by an authorized person
The report has been modified subsequent to being Final, and is complete and verified by an authorized person
The report has been modified subsequent to being Final, and is complete and verified by an authorized person. New content has been added, but existing content hasn't changed
The report is unavailable because the measurement was not started or not completed (also sometimes called "aborted")
The report has been withdrawn following previous Final release

binding.name: AdjunctDiagnosis
binding.definition: Diagnoses codes provided as adjuncts to the report

binding.definition: Codes describing anatomical locations. May include laterality

annotation.definition: A code or name that describes this diagnostic report.
annotation.v2Mapping: OBR-4-Universal Service ID (V2 doesn't provide an easy way to indicate both the ordered test and the performed panel)

annotation.shortDefinition: registered | partial | final | corrected | appended | cancelled | entered-in-error
annotation.definition: The status of the diagnostic report as a whole.
annotation.comment: This is labeled as "Is Modifier" because applications need to take appropriate action if a report is withdrawn.
annotation.requirements: Diagnostic services routinely issue provisional/incomplete reports, and sometimes withdraw previously released reports.
annotation.rimMapping: statusCode Note: final and amended are distinguished by whether observation is the subject of a ControlAct event of type "revise"

annotation.definition: The date and time that this version of the report was released from the source diagnostic service.
annotation.comment: May be different from the update time of the resource itself, because that is the status of the record (potentially a secondary copy), not the actual release time of the report .
annotation.requirements: Clinicians need to be able to check the date that the report was released.

annotation.shortDefinition: The subject of the report, usually, but not always, the patient
annotation.definition: The subject of the report. Usually, but not always, this is a patient. However diagnostic services also perform analyses on specimens collected from a variety of other sources.
annotation.requirements: SHALL know the subject context.
annotation.v2Mapping: PID-3-Patient ID List (no V2 mapping for Group or Device)

annotation.definition: The diagnostic service that is responsible for issuing the report.
annotation.comment: This is not necessarily the source of the atomic data items - it is the entity that takes responsibility for the clinical report.
annotation.requirements: Need to know whom to contact if there are queries about the results. Also may need to track the source of reports for secondary data analysis.

annotation.shortDefinition: Health care event when test ordered
annotation.definition: The link to the health care event (encounter) when the order was made.

annotation.shortDefinition: Id for external references to this report
annotation.definition: The local ID assigned to the report by the order filler, usually by the Information System of the diagnostic service provider.
annotation.requirements: Need to know what identifier to use when making queries about this report from the source laboratory, and for linking to the report outside FHIR context.
annotation.v2Mapping: OBR-51-Observation Group ID (todo: check semantic intent of OBR-51 with OOWG)

annotation.definition: Details concerning a test requested.
annotation.comment: Note: Usually there is one test request for each result, however in some circumstances multiple test requests may be represented using a single test result resource. Note that there are also cases where one request leads to multiple reports.
annotation.requirements: Need to be able to track completion of requests based on reports issued and also to report what diagnostic tests were requested (not always the same as what is delivered).

annotation.definition: The section of the diagnostic service that performs the examination e.g. biochemistry, hematology, MRI.
annotation.requirements: Help clinicians filter/find the reports they are looking for.

annotation.definition: The time or time-period the observed values are related to. When the subject of the report is a patient, this is usually either the time of the procedure or of specimen collection(s), but very often the source of the date/time is not known, only the date/time itself.
annotation.comment: If the diagnostic procedure was performed on the patient, this is the time it was performed. If there are specimens, the diagnostically relevant time can be derived from the specimen collection times, but the specimen information is not always available, and the exact relationship between the specimens and the diagnostically relevant time is not always automatic.
annotation.requirements: Need to know where in the patient history to file/present this report.

annotation.shortDefinition: Specimens this report is based on
annotation.definition: Details about the specimens on which this diagnostic report is based.
annotation.comment: If the specimen is sufficiently specified with a code in the Test result name, then this additional data may be redundant. If there are multiple specimens, these may be represented per Observation or group.
annotation.requirements: Need to be able to report information about the collected specimens on which the report is based.

annotation.shortDefinition: Observations - simple, or complex nested groups
annotation.definition: Observations that are part of this diagnostic report. Observations can be simple name/value pairs (e.g. "atomic" results), or they can be grouping observations that include references to other members of the group (e.g. "panels").
annotation.requirements: Need to be able to individual results, or report groups of results, where the result grouping is arbitrary, but meaningful. This structure is recursive - observations can contain observations.

annotation.shortDefinition: Reference to full details of imaging associated with the diagnostic report
annotation.definition: One or more links to full details of any imaging performed during the diagnostic investigation. Typically, this is imaging performed by DICOM enabled modalities, but this is not required. A fully enabled PACS viewer can use this information to provide views of the source images.
annotation.comment: dImagingStudy and ImageObjectStudy and the image element are somewhat overlapping - typically, the list of image references in the image element will also be found in one of the imaging study resources. However each caters to different types of displays for different types of purposes. Neither, either, or both may be provided.

annotation.shortDefinition: Key images associated with this report
annotation.definition: A list of key images associated with this report. The images are generally created during the diagnostic process, and may be directly of the patient, or of treated specimens (i.e. slides of interest).
annotation.requirements: Many diagnostic services include images in the report as part of their service.

annotation.definition: Concise and clinically contextualized narrative interpretation of the diagnostic report.
annotation.comment: Typically, a report is either [all data, no narrative (e.g. Core lab)] or [a mix of data with some concluding narrative (e.g. Structured Pathology Report, Bone Density)], or [all narrative (e.g. typical imaging report, histopathology)]. In all of these cases, the narrative goes in "text".
annotation.requirements: Need to be able to provide a conclusion that is not lost amongst the basic result data.

annotation.definition: Codes for the conclusion.
Rich text representation of the entire result as issued by the diagnostic service. Multiple formats are allowed but they SHALL be semantically equivalent.
annotation.comment: Application/pdf is recommended as the most reliable and interoperable in this context.
annotation.requirements: Gives Laboratory the ability to provide its own fully formatted report for clinical fidelity.

annotation.shortDefinition: Contents of this set of documents
annotation.definition: The list of DocumentReference or Media Resources, or Attachment that consist of the parts of this document manifest. Usually, these would be document references, but direct references to Media or Attachments are also allowed.

annotations.definition: A nested type in DocumentManifest: Related identifiers or resources associated with the DocumentManifest.

annotation.definition: Related identifier to this DocumentManifest. If both id and ref are present they shall refer to the same thing.
annotation.comment: Order numbers, accession numbers, XDW workflow numbers.

annotation.definition: Related Resource to this DocumentManifest. If both id and ref are present they shall refer to the same thing.
annotation.comment: Order, DiagnosticOrder, Procedure, EligibilityRequest, etc.

binding.definition: Precice type of clinical document

annotation.shortDefinition: Unique Identifier for the set of documents
annotation.definition: A single identifier that uniquely identifies this manifest. Principally used to refer to the manifest in non-FHIR contexts.
annotation.rimMapping: id [need a list semantic to indicate order matters]

annotation.definition: Other identifiers associated with the document manifest, including version independent identifiers.

annotation.shortDefinition: The subject of the set of documents
annotation.definition: Who or what the set of documents is about. The documents can be about a person, (patient or healthcare practitioner), a device (i.e. machine) or even a group of subjects (such as a document about a herd of farm animals, or a set of patients that share a common exposure). If the documents cross more than one subject, then more than one subject is allowed here (unusual use case).

annotation.shortDefinition: Intended to get notified about this set of documents
annotation.definition: A patient, practitioner, or organization for which this set of documents is intended.
annotation.comment: How the recipient receives the document set or is notified of it is up to the implementation. This element is just a statement of intent.

annotation.shortDefinition: What kind of document set this is
annotation.definition: Specifies the kind of this set of documents (e.g. Patient Summary, Discharge Summary, Prescription, etc.). The type of a set of documents may be the same as one of the documents in it - especially if there is only one - but it may be wider.

annotation.shortDefinition: Who and/or what authored the document
annotation.definition: Identifies who is responsible for adding the information to the document.
annotation.comment: Not necessarily who did the actual data entry (i.e. typist) or who was the source (informant).

annotation.definition: When the document manifest was created for submission to the server (not necessarily the same thing as the actual resource last modified time, since it may be modified, replicated etc).
annotation.comment: Creation time is used for tracking, organizing versions and searching. This is the creation time of the document set, not the documents on which it is based.

annotation.definition: Identifies the source system, application, or software that produced the document manifest.
The status of this document manifest.
Human-readable description of the source document. This is sometimes known as the "title".
annotation.comment: What the document is about, rather than a terse summary of the document. It is commonly the case that records do not have a title and are collectively referred to by the display name of Record code (e.g. a "consultation" or "progress note").
annotation.requirements: Helps humans to assess whether the document is of interest.

annotation.definition: The manifest list.
Related identifiers or resources associated with the DocumentManifest.
annotation.comment: May be identifiers or resources that caused the DocumentManifest to be created.

annotations.shortDefinition: A reference to a document
annotations.definition: A reference to a document.
annotations.comment: Usually, this is used for documents other than those defined by FHIR.

annotations.definition: A nested type in DocumentReference: The clinical context in which the document was prepared.

annotation.definition: This list of codes represents the main clinical acts, such as a colonoscopy or an appendectomy, being documented. In some cases, the event is inherent in the typeCode, such as a "History and Physical Report" in which the procedure being documented is necessarily a "History and Physical" act.
annotation.comment: An event can further specialize the act inherent in the type, such as where it is simply "Procedure Report" and the procedure was a "colonoscopy". If one or more event codes are included, they shall not conflict with the values inherent in the class or type elements as such a conflict would create an ambiguous situation.

annotation.shortDefinition: Time of service that is being documented
annotation.definition: The time period over which the service that is described by the document was provided.

annotation.shortDefinition: Kind of facility where patient was seen
annotation.definition: The kind of facility where the patient was seen.

annotation.shortDefinition: Additional details about where the content was created (e.g. clinical specialty)
annotation.definition: This property may convey specifics about the practice setting where the content was created, often reflecting the clinical specialty.
annotation.comment: The value set for this content has an example binding because it is a value set decided by community policy. Other examples exist for consideration: * HITSP created the table HITSP/C80 Table 2-148 Clinical Specialty Value Set (a value set based upon SNOMED-CT which is referenced by Direct (XDR and XDM for Direct Messaging Specification, Version 1), as well as Nationwide Health Information Network (NHIN). Query for Documents, Web Service Interface Specification, V 3.0, 07/27/2011 * ELGA (Austria) (ELGA CDA Implementie-rungsleitfden Registrierung von CDA Dokumenten fr ELGA mit IHE Cross-Enterprise Document Sharing: XDS Metadaten (XDSDocumentEntry), [1.2.40.0.34.7.6.3] * XDS Connect-a-thon practiceSettingCode.
annotation.requirements: This is an important piece of metadata that providers often rely upon to quickly sort and/or filter out to find specific content.

annotation.definition: The Patient Information as known when the document was published. May be a reference to a version specific, or contained.

annotation.comment: If this document appends another document, then the document cannot be fully understood without also accessing the referenced document.

annotation.definition: Document identifier as assigned by the source of the document. This identifier is specific to this version of the document. This unique identifier may be used elsewhere to identify this version of the document.
annotation.comment: CDA Document Id extension and root.
annotation.requirements: The structure and format of this Id shall be consistent with the specification corresponding to the formatCode attribute. (e.g., for a DICOM standard document a 64 character numeric UID, for an HL7 CDA format a serialization of the CDA Document Id extension and root in the form oid^extension, where OID is a 64 digits max, and the Id is a 16 UTF-8 char max. If the OID is coded without the extension then the '^' character shall not be included.).

annotation.definition: Other identifiers associated with the document, including version independent identifiers.

annotation.shortDefinition: Who|what is the subject of the document
annotation.definition: Who or what the document is about. The document can be about a person, (patient or healthcare practitioner), a device (I.e. machine) or even a group of subjects (such as a document about a herd of farm animals, or a set of patients that share a common exposure).
annotation.v2Mapping: PID-3-Patient ID List (No standard way to define a Practitioner or Group subject in V2 MDM message)

annotation.definition: Specifies the particular kind of document. This usually equates to the purpose of making the document. It is recommended that the value Set be drawn from a coding scheme providing a fine level of granularity such as LOINC. (e.g. Patient Summary, Discharge Summary, Prescription, etc.).
annotation.comment: Key metadata element describing the document, used in searching/filtering.

annotation.definition: A categorization for the type of document - helps for indexing and searching. This may be implied by or derived from the code specified in the Composition Type.
annotation.comment: This is a metadata field from [XDS/MHD](http://wiki.ihe.net/index.php?title=Mobile_access_to_Health_Documents_(MHD)).
annotation.requirements: Helps humans to assess whether the document is of interest when viewing an list of documents.

annotation.definition: An identifier of the document encoding, structure, and template that the document conforms to beyond the base format indicated in the mimeType.
annotation.comment: Helps the processing. Usually is a URN that identifies. For IHE defined Document Content profiles this is a urn issued by IHE.

annotation.shortDefinition: Who and/or what authored the document
annotation.definition: Identifies who is responsible for adding the information to the document.
annotation.comment: Not necessarily who did the actual data entry (i.e. typist) it in or who was the source (informant).
annotation.v2Mapping: TXA-9-Originator Code/Name (No standard way to indicate a Device in V2 MDM message)

annotation.definition: Identifies the organization or group who is responsible for ongoing maintenance of and access to the document.
annotation.comment: Identifies the logical organization to go to find the current version, where to report issues, etc. This is different from the physical location of the document, which is the technical location of the document, which host may be delegated to the management of some other organization.

annotation.definition: Which person or organization authenticates that this document is valid.
annotation.comment: Represents a participant within the author institution who has legally authenticated or attested the document. Legal authentication implies that a document has been signed manually or electronically by the legal Authenticator.

annotation.definition: When the document was created.
annotation.comment: Creation time is used for tracking, organizing versions and searching. This is the creation time of the document, not the source material on which it is based.

annotation.definition: When the document reference was created.
annotation.comment: Referencing/indexing time is used for tracking, organizing versions and searching.

annotation.definition: The status of this document reference.
annotation.comment: This is the status of the DocumentReference object, which might be independent from the docStatus.
annotation.rimMapping: interim: .completionCode="IN" & ./statusCode[isNormalDatatype()]="active"; final: .completionCode="AU" && ./statusCode[isNormalDatatype()]="complete" and not(./inboundRelationship[typeCode="SUBJ" and isNormalActRelationship()]/source[subsumesCode("ActClass#CACT") and moodCode="EVN" and domainMember("ReviseDocument", code) and isNormalAct()]); amended: .completionCode="AU" && ./statusCode[isNormalDatatype()]="complete" and ./inboundRelationship[typeCode="SUBJ" and isNormalActRelationship()]/source[subsumesCode("ActClass#CACT") and moodCode="EVN" and domainMember("ReviseDocument", code) and isNormalAct() and statusCode="completed"]; withdrawn : .completionCode=NI && ./statusCode[isNormalDatatype()]="obsolete"

annotation.definition: The status of the underlying document.
annotation.comment: The document that is pointed to might be in various lifecycle states.

annotation.definition: Relationships that this document has with other document references that already exist.
Human-readable description of the source document. This is sometimes known as the "title".
annotation.comment: What the document is about, rather than a terse summary of the document. It is commonly the case that records do not have a title and are collectively referred to by the display name of Record code (e.g. a "consultation" or "progress note").
annotation.requirements: Helps humans to assess whether the document is of interest.

annotation.definition: A set of Security-Tag codes specifying the level of privacy/security of the Document.
annotation.comment: The confidentiality codes can carry multiple vocabulary items. HL7 has developed an understanding of security and privacy tags that might be desirable in a Document Sharing environment, called HL7 Healthcare Privacy and Security Classification System (HCS). The following specification is recommended but not mandated, as the vocabulary bindings are an administrative domain responsibility. The use of this method is up to the policy domain such as the XDS Affinity Domain or other Trust Domain where all parties including sender and recipients are trusted to appropriately tag and enforce. [11] Confidentiality Security Classification Label Field [0*] Sensitivity Security Category Label Field [0*] Compartment Security Category Label Field [0*] Integrity Security Category Label Field [0*] Handling Caveat Security Category Field In the HL7 Healthcare Privacy and Security Classification System In the HL7 Healthcare Privacy and Security Classification (HCS) there are code systems specific to Confidentiality, Sensitivity, Integrity, and Handling Caveats. Some values would come from a local vocabulary as they are related to workflow roles and special projects.
annotation.requirements: Use of the Health Care Privacy/Security Classification (HCS) system of security-tag use is recommended.

annotation.definition: The document or url to the document along with critical metadata to prove content has integrity.
The clinical context in which the document was prepared.
