annotations.definition: A set of DICOM SOP Instances of a patient, selected for some application purpose, e.g., quality assurance, teaching, conference, consulting, etc. Objects selected can be from different studies, but must be of the same patient.
annotations.requirements: A FHIR representation of DICOM Key Object Selection (KOS) SOP Instances enables access to a set of selected DICOM SOP Instances.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImagingObjectSelection: Study identity and locating information of the DICOM SOP instances in the selection.

annotation.definition: Study instance uid of the SOP instances in the selection.
annotation.requirements: Study instance uid is required to fully identify the DICOM SOP instances in the selection.

annotation.definition: WADO-RS URL to retrieve the study. Note that this URL retrieves all SOP instances of the study, not only those in the selection.
annotation.comment: Study level locator information is optional. If provided, this is the URL to retrieve the entire study with WADO-RS interaction, though only a subset of these are selected in the selection.
annotation.requirements: WADO-RS URL enables retrieval of the entire study using DICOM WADO-RS API.

annotation.shortDefinition: Series identity of the selected instances
annotation.definition: Series indetity and locating information of the DICOM SOP instances in the selection.
annotation.comment: Series component represents the series level indentity and locator information of the DICOM SOP instances in the selection.
annotation.requirements: DICOM SOP instances are identified through the UIDs of the study - series - instance hierarchy. In addition, the locator at the series level provide a means of retrieving the entire series.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImagingObjectSelection: Series indetity and locating information of the DICOM SOP instances in the selection.

annotation.definition: Series instance uid of the SOP instances in the selection.
annotation.requirements: Series instance uid is required to fully identify the DICOM SOP instances in the selection.

annotation.definition: WADO-RS URL to retrieve the series Note that this URL retrieves all SOP instances of the series not only those in the selection.
annotation.comment: Series level locator information is optional. If provided, this is the URL to retrieve the entire series with WADO-RS interaction, though only a subset of these are selected in the selection.
annotation.requirements: WADO-RS URL enables retrieval of the entire series using DICOM WADO-RS API.

annotation.definition: Identity and locating information of the selected DICOM SOP instances.
annotation.comment: SOP Instance component identify the instance selected in the selection, along with the study and series identities to form the DICOM identity hierachy.
annotation.requirements: DICOM SOP instances are identified through the UIDs of the study - series - instance hierarchy. This is the instance level identity of the instance in the selection.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImagingObjectSelection: Identity and location information of the frames in the selected instance.

annotation.definition: The frame numbers in the frame set.
annotation.requirements: one or more non duplicate frame numbers.

annotation.definition: WADO-RS URL to retrieve the DICOM frames.
annotation.comment: Frame level locator information is required.
annotation.requirements: WADO-RS URL enables retrieval of the frames using DICOM WADO-RS API.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImagingObjectSelection: Identity and locating information of the selected DICOM SOP instances.

annotation.definition: SOP class uid of the selected instance.
annotation.comment: SOP class uid provides the type of the selected instances, e.g., CT image, Gray scale softcopy presentation state, ECG waveform, etc.
annotation.requirements: DICOM SOP instance can be an imaging or other data object. The SOP class uid provide the accurate information about what type the instance is.
annotation.committeeNotes: Define proficiency and mode as extensions.

annotation.definition: SOP Instance uid of the selected instance.
annotation.comment: SOP instance uid identifies the instance.
annotation.requirements: SOP instance uid is required to fully identify the DICOM SOP instance in the selection.
annotation.committeeNotes: Rationale for putting this in the core is based on input from Canada. Other persons on call are from single language countries. Committee felt uncomfortable with leaving any of the 3 optional attributes modeCode, proficiencyLevelCode, or preferenceInd up to extensions. Instead we said that isModifier is "no" on modeCode and preferenceInd.

annotation.definition: WADO-RS URL to retrieve the DICOM SOP Instance.
annotation.comment: Instance level locator information is required.
annotation.requirements: WADO-RS URL enables retrieval of the SOP instance using DICOM WADO-RS API.

annotation.definition: Identity and location information of the frames in the selected instance.
annotation.comment: This component may be used if the referenced image SOP Instance is a multi-frame image.
annotation.requirements: The DICOM frames for a given study, series, SOP Instance UID, and frame numbers. The retrieveUrl retrieves the pixel data, and is encapsulated in a multipart MIME response.

binding.name: KOStitle
binding.definition: The document title code of key object selection

annotation.definition: Instance UID of the DICOM KOS SOP Instances represenetd in this resource.
annotation.requirements: DICOM SOP Instance is always assigned with a unique identifier (UID).

annotation.definition: A patient resource reference which is the patient subject of all DICOM SOP Instances in this key object selection.
annotation.comment: SOP instances selected in the key object selection can be from different studies, but must be of the same patient.
annotation.requirements: SOP Instances in key object selection must be from the same patient.

annotation.definition: The reason for, or significance of, the selection of objects referenced in the resource.
annotation.comment:
Coded concept of kind of the key object selection. Value set is defined in the DICOM standard CID-7010.
http://medical.nema.org/medical/dicom/current/output/chtml/part16/sect_CID_7010.html.
annotation.requirements: Need to represent the application purpose that the SOP instances in key object selection are selected for.

annotation.definition: Text description of the DICOM SOP instances selected in the key object selection. This should be aligned with the content of the title element, and can provide further explanation of the SOP instances in the selection.
annotation.comment: Free text narrative description of the key object selection.
annotation.requirements: Need to provide a narrative description of the SOP instances in the selection.

annotation.definition: Author of key object selection. It can be a human authtor or a device which made the decision of the SOP instances selected. For example, a radiologist selected a set of imaging SOP instances to attached in a diagnostic report, and a CAD application may author a selection to describe SOP instances it used to generate a detection conclusion.
annotation.comment: Author of the key object selection. This can be a human author or a device author. Human author is represented with the HumanName type. Device author is represented with a reference to the Device resource.
annotation.requirements: Track the selection decision maker.

annotation.definition: Date and time when the key object selection was authored. Note that this is the date and time the DICOM SOP instances in the selection were selected (selection decision making). It is different from the creation date and time of the selection resource.
annotation.comment: Authoring time.
annotation.requirements: Date and time when the selection was made can be important to understand the content of selection.

annotation.shortDefinition: Study identity of the selected instances
annotation.definition: Study identity and locating information of the DICOM SOP instances in the selection.
annotation.comment: Study component represents the study level identity and locator information of the DICOM SOP instances in the selection. It is the top level identity of the hierachical identification of the instances.
annotation.requirements: DICOM SOP instances are identified through the UIDs of the study - series - instance hierarchy. In addition, the locator at the study level provide a means of retrieving the entire study.

annotations.shortDefinition: A set of images produced in single study (one or more series of references images)
annotations.definition: Representation of the content produced in a DICOM imaging study. A study comprises a set of Series, each of which includes a set of Service-Object Pair Instances (SOP Instances - images or other data) acquired or produced in a common context. A Series is of only one modality (e.g., X-ray, CT, MR, ultrasound), but a Study may have multiple Series of different modalities.
A nested type in ImagingStudy: Each study has one or more series of image instances.

annotation.definition: The Numeric identifier of this series in the study.

annotation.shortDefinition: The modality of the instances in the series (0008,0060)
annotation.definition: The modality of this series sequence.
Formal identifier for this series.
A description of the series.
Number of SOP Instances in Series.
Availability of series (online, offline or nearline).

annotation.shortDefinition: Location of the referenced instance(s) (0008,1115 in 0008,1190)
annotation.definition: URI/URL specifying the location of the referenced series using WADO-RS.
Body part examined. See DICOM Part 16 Annex L for the mapping from DICOM to Snomed.
Laterality if bodySite is paired anatomic structure and laterality is not pre-coordinated in bodySite code, map from (0020, 0060).
The date and time when the series was started.

annotation.shortDefinition: A single instance taken from a patient (image or other)
annotation.definition: A single SOP Instance within the series, e.g., an image, or presentation state.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImagingStudy: A single SOP Instance within the series, e.g., an image, or presentation state.

annotation.shortDefinition: The number of this instance in the series (0020,0013)
annotation.definition: The number of this image in the series.
Formal identifier for this image.
DICOM Image type.
A human-friendly SOP Class name.
annotation.comment: E.g., 'CT image', 'MR multi-frame', 'blending presentation'.

annotation.definition: The description of the instance.
annotation.comment: Particularly for post-acquisition analytic objects, such as SR, presentation states, value mapping, etc.

annotation.definition: Content of the instance or a rendering thereof (e.g., a JPEG of an image, or an XML of a structured report). May be represented by inline encoding, or by a URL reference to a WADO-RS service that makes the instance available. Multiple content attachments may be used for alternate representations of the instance.
annotation.comment: Each instance may have a url and an attachment. Both represent the same information, but using different approaches. The attachment is a reference to a FHIR resource (Media, Document, etc).

The requesting/referring physician.

annotations.shortDefinition: A set of rules about how FHIR is used
annotations.definition: A set of rules or how FHIR is used to solve a particular problem. This resource is used to gather all the parts of an implementation guide into a logical whole, and to publish a computable definition of all the parts.
annotations.requirements: An implementation guide is able to define default profiles that must apply to any use of a resource, so validation services may need to take one or more implementation guide resources when validating.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImplementationGuide: A default profile that applies to a particular resource type. Whenever a resource type is referenced in any structure definition (explicitly, or by inheritance from the base specification), and no explicit profile is applied, then this default profile applies.

annotation.shortDefinition: Type of resource default applies to
annotation.definition: The type of resource that this default applies to.
The profile (StructureDefinition resource) that applies by default.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImplementationGuide: A logical set of resources that is a section in the implementation Guide.

annotation.definition: A human readable name that introduces the item.
annotation.comment: Primarily defined for publishing purposes.

annotation.shortDefinition: An item in the section / package
annotation.definition: An item in the set of resources that is a section in the implementation Guide.
An html page that is published with the Implementation Guide, as part of the package.
annotation.requirements: Added to support using the ImplementationGuide resource to drive publication of the IG, and so that tools that work with the IG contents are aware of the html pages that are in the guide.
annotation.committeeNotes: Problem of order between pages and examples?

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImplementationGuide: An html page that is published with the Implementation Guide.

annotation.definition: A URL that identifies the html page.

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImplementationGuide: If the item is a structure definition, an example that conforms to the structure definition.

annotation.definition: A human readable name that introduces the example.
A reference to a resource that is an example for a structure definition.

annotation.definition: Additional text that explains why the example was provided (e.g. what to look for in it).

annotation.definition: A human readable name that introduces the package.
annotation.comment: Primarily defined for publishing purposes.

annotation.committeeNotes: This means, no examples without a structure definition?

annotations.definition: A nested type in ImplementationGuide: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.

annotation.definition: The name of an individual to contact regarding the implementation guide.
annotation.comment: If there is no named individual, the telecom is for the organization as a whole.

annotation.shortDefinition: Contact details for individual or publisher
annotation.definition: Contact details for individual (if a name was provided) or the publisher.

binding.name: PagePurpose
binding.definition: Codes that specifies how the page is used in the IG

code.definition: The home page - the start page for the appendix

binding.name: ImplementationGuideCode
binding.definition: Codes for the meaning of the defined structure (SNOMED CT and LOINC codes, as an example)

annotation.shortDefinition: Literal URL used to reference this Implementation Guide
annotation.definition: An absolute URL that is used to identify this implementation guide when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or an instance. This SHALL be a URL, SHOULD be globally unique, and SHOULD be an address at which this implementation guide is (or will be) published.
annotation.requirements: This is required to allow hosting Implementation Guides on multiple different servers, and to allow for the editorial process.

annotation.shortDefinition: Logical id for this version of the Implementation Guide
annotation.definition: The identifier that is used to identify this version of the Implementation Guide when it is referenced in a specification, model, design or instance. This is an arbitrary value managed by the Implementation Guide author manually.
annotation.requirements: There may be multiple resource versions of the Implementation Guide that have this same identifier. The resource version id will change for technical reasons, whereas the stated version number needs to be under the author's control.

annotation.shortDefinition: Informal name for this Implementation Guide
annotation.definition: A free text natural language name identifying the Implementation Guide.
annotation.comment: Not expected to be globally unique.

annotation.shortDefinition: The implementation guide is intended to support these contexts
annotation.definition: The content was developed with a focus and intent of supporting the contexts that are listed. These terms may be used to assist with indexing and searching of implementation guides. The most common use of this element is to represent the country / jurisdication for which this implementation guide was defined.
annotation.requirements: Assist in searching for appropriate implementation guide.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of the publisher (Organization or individual)
annotation.definition: The name of the individual or organization that published the implementation guide.
annotation.comment: Usually an organization, but may be an individual. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.
annotation.requirements: Helps establish the "authority/credibility" of the implementation guide. May also allow for contact.

annotation.definition: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.
annotation.comment: May be a web site, an email address, a telephone number (tel:), etc.

annotation.shortDefinition: Natural language description of the Implementation Guide
annotation.definition: A free text natural language description of the Implementation Guide and its use.
annotation.comment: This field can be used for things such as why the Implementation Guide was written, comments about misuse, instructions for clinical use and interpretation, literature references, examples from the paper world, etc. It is *not* a rendering of the Implementation Guide as conveyed in Implementation Guide.text. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.

annotation.definition: A copyright statement relating to the implementation guide and/or its contents. Copyright statements are generally legal restrictions on the use and publishing of the details of the constraints and mappings.
A set of terms from external terminologies that may be used to assist with indexing and searching of templates.
annotation.requirements: Assist in searching for appropriate ImplementationGuides.

annotation.definition: The status of the Implementation Guide.
annotation.requirements: Allows filtering of Implementation Guides that are appropriate for use vs. not.

annotation.shortDefinition: If for testing purposes, not real usage
annotation.definition: This Implementation Guide was authored for testing purposes (or education/evaluation/marketing), and is not intended to be used for genuine usage.
annotation.requirements: Allows filtering of Implementation Guides that are appropriate for use vs. not.

annotation.shortDefinition: Date for this version of the Implementation Guide
annotation.definition: The date that this version of the Implementation Guide was published.

annotation.shortDefinition: FHIR Version this Implementation Guide targets
annotation.definition: The version of the FHIR specification on which this ImplementationGuide is based - this is the formal version of the specification, without the revision number, e.g. [publication].[major].[minor], which is 0.5.0 for this version.
annotation.comment: A Implementation Guide should specify the target it applies to, as ImplementationGuides are rarely valid across multiple versions of FHIR.

annotation.definition: An html page that is published with the Implementation Guide.
annotation.requirements: Added to support using the ImplementationGuide resource to drive publication of the IG, and so that tools that work with the IG contents are aware of the html pages that are in the guide.

annotation.definition: A logical set of resources that is a section in the implementation Guide.
annotation.comment: Many Implementation Guides have a single package.

annotation.shortDefinition: Applies when no explicit profile applied
annotation.definition: A default profile that applies to a particular resource type. Whenever a resource type is referenced in any structure definition (explicitly, or by inheritance from the base specification), and no explicit profile is applied, then this default profile applies.

annotation.definition: The flag allows the system constructing the list to make one or more statements about the role and significance of the item in the list.

annotation.shortDefinition: If this item is actually marked as deleted
annotation.definition: True if this item is marked as deleted in the list.
annotation.comment: If the flag means that the entry has actually been deleted from the list, the deleted element SHALL be true. Both flag and deleted can only be used if the List.mode is "changes". A deleted entry should be displayed in narrative as deleted.
annotation.requirements: The flag element may contain codes that an application processing the list does not understand. However there can be no ambiguity if a list item is actually marked as "deleted".

annotation.definition: When this item was added to the list.
annotation.comment: This is only useful and meaningful when the mode is "working".
annotation.requirements: The date may be significant for understanding the meaning of items in a working list.

annotation.definition: A reference to the actual resource from which data was derived.

binding.name: ListItemFlag
binding.definition: Codes that provide further information about the reason and meaning of the item in the list

code.definition: No change has been made to the status of this medicine item.
The medicine item has changed. The change may be described in an extension (not defined yet)

The prescription for this medicine item was cancelled by an authorized health care provider. The patient may be advised to complete the course of the prescribed medicine. This advice is a clinical decision made based on assessment of the patients clinical condition.
A new medicine item has been prescribed

Administration of this medication item that the patient is currently taking is stopped or recommended to be stopped (i.e. instructed to be ceased by a health care provider). This cessation is anticipated to be permanent. The Change Description should describe the reason for cessation. Example uses: the medication in question is considered ineffective or has caused serious adverse effects. This value applies both to the cessation of a medication that is prescribed by another healthcare provider or patient self-administration of OTC medicines.

Administration of this medication item that the patient is currently taking is on hold, or instructed or recommended by a health care provider to be temporarily stopped, or subject to clinical review (i.e. the stop may be temporary or permanent depending on the outcome of clinical review), or temporarily suspended as a pre-requisite to certain surgical or diagnostic procedures.

binding.name: ListEmptyReason
binding.definition: If a list is empty, why it is empty

code.definition: Clinical judgement that there are no known items for this list after reasonable investigation. Note that this a positive statement by a clinical user, and not a default position asserted by a computer system in the lack of other information. Example uses: * For allergies: the patient or patient's agent/guardian has asserted that he/she is not aware of any allergies (NKA - nil known allergies) * For medications: the patient or patient's agent/guardian has asserted that the patient is known to be taking no medications * For diagnoses, problems and procedures: the patient or patient's agent/guardian has asserted that there is no known event to record.
code.comment: Other language is sometimes used for this concept, such as 'no significant [x] known'. SNOMED CT includes many codes for this general concept, but no single generalisation. If using SNOMED CT, use this code and the appropriate specific SNOMED CT code

code.definition: THe investigation to find out whether there are items for this list has not occurred

Information was not provided due to privacy or confidentiality concerns. Note that it should not be assumed that this means that the particular information in question was withheld due to its contents - it can also be a policy decision
code.comment: In spite of the definition, this code should be used carefully as it represents potential information leakage or the perception thereof

code.definition: Information to populate this list cannot be obtained. E.g. unconscious patient
The work to populate this list has not yet begun
This list has now closed or has ceased to be relevant or useful

binding.name: ListOrder
binding.definition: What order applies to the items in a list

code.definition: The list was sorted by a user. The criteria the user used are not specified
The list was sorted by the system. The criteria the user used are not specified; define additional codes to specify a particular order (or use other defined codes)
The list is sorted by the data of the event. This can be used when the list has items which are dates with past or future events
The list is sorted by the date the item was added to the list. Note that the date added to the list is not explicit in the list itself
The list is sorted by priority. The exact method in which priority has been determined is not specified
The list is sorted alphabetically by an unspecified property of the items in the list
The list is sorted categorically by an unspecified property of the items in the list
The list is sorted by patient, with items for each patient grouped together

binding.name: ListStatus
binding.definition: The current state of the list

code.definition: The list is considered to be an active part of the patient's record.
The list is "old" and should no longer be considered accurate or relevant.
The list was never accurate. It is retained for medico-legal purposes only.

binding.name: ListMode
binding.definition: The processing mode that applies to this list

code.definition: This list is the master list, maintained in an ongoing fashion with regular updates as the real world list it is tracking changes
This list was prepared as a snapshot. It should not be assumed to be current
A list that indicates where changes have been made or recommended

binding.name: ListPurpose
binding.definition: What the purpose of a list is

code.definition: A list of alerts for the patient
A list of part adverse reactions
A list of Allergies for the patient
A list of medication statements for the patient
A list of problems that the patient is known of have (or have had in the past)
A list of items that constitute a set of work to be performed (typically this code would be specialised for more specific uses, such as a ward round list)
A list of items waiting for an event (perhaps a surgical patient waiting list)
A set of protocols to be followed
A set of care plans that apply in a particular context of care

annotation.definition: Identifier for the List assigned for business purposes outside the context of FHIR.
A label for the list assigned by the author.
annotation.requirements: Allows customization beyond just the code identifying the kind of list.

annotation.shortDefinition: What the purpose of this list is
annotation.definition: This code defines the purpose of the list - why it was created.
annotation.comment: If there is no code, the purpose of the list is implied where it is used, such as in a document section using Document.section.code.
annotation.requirements: Lists often contain subsets of resources rather than an exhaustive list. The code identifies what type of subset is included.

annotation.shortDefinition: If all resources have the same subject
annotation.definition: The common subject (or patient) of the resources that are in the list, if there is one.
annotation.comment: Some purely aribitrary lists do not have a common subject, so this is optional.
annotation.requirements: The primary purpose of listing the subject explicitly is to help with finding the right list.

annotation.shortDefinition: Who and/or what defined the list contents (aka Author)
annotation.definition: The entity responsible for deciding what the contents of the list were. Where the list was created by a human, this is the same as the author of the list.
annotation.comment: The primary source is the entity that made the decisions what items are in the list. This may be software or user.
annotation.requirements: Allows follow-up as well as context.

annotation.definition: The encounter that is the context in which this list was created.
Indicates the current state of this list.
The date that the list was prepared.
annotation.comment: The actual important date is the date of currency of the resources that were summarized, but it is usually assumed that these are current when the preparation occurs.
annotation.requirements: Identifies how current the list is which affects relevance.

annotation.definition: What order applies to the items in the list.
annotation.comment: Applications SHOULD render ordered lists in the order provided, but MAY allow users to re-order based on their own preferences as well. If there is no order specified, the order is unknown, though there may still be some order.
annotation.requirements: Important for presentation and rendering. Lists may be sorted to place more important information first or to group related entries.

annotation.definition: How this list was prepared - whether it is a working list that is suitable for being maintained on an ongoing basis, or if it represents a snapshot of a list of items from another source, or whether it is a prepared list where items may be marked as added, modified or deleted.
annotation.requirements: Lists are used in various ways, and it must be known in what way it is safe to use them.

annotation.definition: Comments that apply to the overall list.
Entries in this list.
annotation.comment: If there are no entries in the list, an emptyReason SHOULD be provided.

annotation.definition: If the list is empty, why the list is empty.
annotation.comment: The various reasons for an empty list make a significant interpretation to its interpretation.
annotation.requirements: Allows capturing things like "none exist" or "not asked" which can be important for most lists.

annotations.shortDefinition: Administration of medication to a patient
annotations.definition:
Describes the event of a patient consuming or otherwise being administered a medication. This may be as simple as swallowing a tablet or it may be a long running infusion.
Related resources tie this event to the authorizing prescription, and the specific encounter between patient and health care practitioner.
A nested type in MedicationAdministration: Indicates how the medication is/was used by the patient.

annotation.definition: Free text dosage instructions can be used for cases where the instructions are too complex to code. When coded instructions are present, the free text instructions may still be present for display to humans taking or administering the medication.
A coded specification of the anatomic site where the medication first entered the body. E.g. "left arm".
A code specifying the route or physiological path of administration of a therapeutic agent into or onto the patient. E.g. topical, intravenous, etc.

A coded value indicating the method by which the medication was introduced into or onto the body. Most commonly used for injections. Examples: Slow Push; Deep IV.
Terminologies used often pre-coordinate this term with the route and or form of administration.
The amount of the medication given at one administration event. Use this value when the administration is essentially an instantaneous event such as a swallowing a tablet or giving an injection.
annotation.comment: If the administration is not instantaneous (rate is present or timing has a duration), this can be specified to convey the total amount administered over period of time of a single administration (as indicated by schedule).
annotation.v2Mapping: RXA-6-Administered Amount / RXA-7.1-Administered Units.code / RXA-7.3-Administered Units.name of coding system (uri<->code system mapping required)

annotation.shortDefinition: Dose quantity per unit of time
annotation.definition: Identifies the speed with which the medication was introduced into the patient. Typically the rate for an infusion e.g. 200ml in 2 hours. May also be expressed as a rate per unit of time such as 100ml per hour - the duration is then not specified, or is specified in the quantity.
annotation.comment: If the rate changes over time, each change should be captured as a distinct "dosage" repetition. This element should *not* be used to convey an average rate.

binding.name: MedicationAdministrationReason

The administration was needed to treat an emergency

code.definition: The administration has started but has not yet completed.

The administration was entered in error and therefore nullified.
Actions implied by the administration have been permanently halted, before all of them occurred.

annotation.definition: External identifier - FHIR will generate its own internal IDs (probably URLs) which do not need to be explicitly managed by the resource. The identifier here is one that would be used by another non-FHIR system - for example an automated medication pump would provide a record each time it operated; an administration while the patient was off the ward might be made with a different system and entered after the event. Particularly important if these records have to be updated.

The person or animal to whom the medication was given.
The individual who was responsible for giving the medication to the patient.

annotation.v2Mapping: RXA-3-Date/Time Start of Administration / RXA-4-Date/Time End of Administration
annotation.committeeNotes: 2014-0917 HG: Chjanged name from whenGiven to effectiveTime and made datatype choice of period or dataTime.

annotation.shortDefinition: Time period supply is authorized for
annotation.definition: Design Comments: This indicates the validity period of a prescription (stale dating the Prescription) It reflects the prescriber perspective for the validity of the prescription. Dispenses must not be made against the prescription outside of this period. The lower-bound of the Dispensing Window signifies the earliest date that the prescription can be filled for the first time. If an upper-bound is not specified then the Prescription is open-ended or will default to a stale-date based on regulations. Rationale: Indicates when the Prescription becomes valid, and when it ceases to be a dispensable Prescription.

annotations.shortDefinition: A resource that describes a message that is exchanged between systems
annotations.definition: The header for a message exchange that is either requesting or responding to an action. The Reference(s) that are the subject of the action as well as other Information related to the action are typically transmitted in a bundle in which the MessageHeader resource instance is the first resource in the bundle.
annotations.requirements: Many implementations are not prepared to use REST and need a messaging based infrastructure.

annotations.definition: A nested type in MessageHeader: The destination application which the message is intended for.

annotation.definition: Human-readable name for the target system.
annotation.requirements: May be used for routing of response and/or to support audit.

annotation.shortDefinition: Particular delivery destination within the destination
annotation.definition: Identifies the target end system in situations where the initial message transmission is to an intermediary system.
annotation.requirements: Supports multi-hop routing.

annotation.definition: Indicates where the message should be routed to.
annotation.comment: The id may be a non-resolvable URI for systems that do not use standard network-based addresses.
annotation.requirements: Identifies where to route the message.
annotation.v2Mapping: MSH-25-receiving network address (or MSH-6-receiving facility by implication)

annotations.definition: A nested type in MessageHeader: The source application from which this message originated.

annotation.definition: Human-readable name for the source system.
annotation.requirements: May be used to support audit.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of software running the system
annotation.definition: May include configuration or other information useful in debugging.
annotation.requirements: Supports audit and possibly interface engine behavior.

annotation.definition: Can convey versions of multiple systems in situations where a message passes through multiple hands.
annotation.requirements: Supports audit and possibly interface engine behavior.
annotation.v2Mapping: SFT-2-software certified version or release number
annotation.committeeNotes: Version is not captured as a distinct property in v3.

annotation.definition: An e-mail, phone, website or other contact point to use to resolve issues with message communications.
annotation.requirements: Allows escalation of technical issues.
annotation.rimMapping: unique(./entity[determinerCode="INST" and classCode="DEV"]/scopesRole[normalRole() and classCode="CON" and layer[classCode="PSN"]/telecom[isNormalDatatype()])
annotation.committeeNotes: Should actually have a code for the role in the v3 mapping to indicate that the contact is for "problems".

annotation.shortDefinition: Actual message source address or id
annotation.definition: Identifies the routing target to send acknowledgements to.
annotation.comment: The id may be a non-resolvable URI for systems that do not use standard network-based addresses.
annotation.requirements: Identifies where to send responses, may influence security permissions.

annotations.definition: A nested type in MessageHeader: Information about the message that this message is a response to. Only present if this message is a response.

annotation.definition: The id of the message that this message is a response to.
annotation.requirements: Allows receiver to know what message is being responded to.

annotation.definition: Code that identifies the type of response to the message - whether it was successful or not, and whether it should be resent or not.
annotation.comment: This is a generic response to the request message. Specific data for the response will be found in MessageHeader.data.
annotation.requirements: Allows the sender of the acknowledge message to know if the request was successful or if action is needed.

annotation.definition: Full details of any issues found in the message.
annotation.comment: This SHALL be contained in the bundle. If any of the issues are errors, the response code SHALL be an error.
annotation.requirements: Allows the sender of the message to determine what the specific issues are.

binding.name: EventReason
binding.definition: Reason for event occurrence

code.definition: The patient has temporarily left the institution
The patient has returned from a temporary absence
The patient has been moved to a new location
Encounter details have been updated (e.g. to correct a coding error)

binding.name: ResponseType
binding.definition: The kind of response to a message

code.definition: The message was accepted and processed without error

Some internal unexpected error occurred - wait and try again. Note - this is usually used for things like database unavailable, which may be expected to resolve, though human intervention may be required
The message was rejected because of some content in it. There is no point in re-sending without change. The response narrative SHALL describe what the issue is.

annotation.definition: The identifier of this message.
annotation.comment: This SHALL be unique within the scope of this stream of messages.

annotation.shortDefinition: Time that the message was sent
annotation.definition: The time that the message was sent.
annotation.requirements: Allows limited detection of out-of-order and delayed transmission. Also supports audit.

annotation.shortDefinition: Code for the event this message represents
annotation.definition: Code that identifies the event this message represents and connects it with its definition. Events defined as part of the FHIR specification have the system value "http://hl7.org/fhir/message-events".
annotation.requirements: Drives the behavior associated with this message.

annotation.shortDefinition: If this is a reply to prior message
annotation.definition: Information about the message that this message is a response to. Only present if this message is a response.
The source application from which this message originated.
annotation.requirements: Allows replies, supports audit.

annotation.definition: The destination application which the message is intended for.
annotation.comment: there SHOULD be at least one destination, but in some circumstances, the source system is unaware of any particular destination system.
annotation.requirements: Indicates where message is to be sent to for routing purposes. Allows verification of "am I the intended recipient".

annotation.shortDefinition: The source of the data entry
annotation.definition: The person or device that performed the data entry leading to this message. Where there is more than one candidate, pick the most proximal to the message. Can provide other enterers in extensions.
annotation.comment: Usually only for the request, but can be used in a response.
annotation.requirements: Need to know for audit/traceback requirements and possibly for authorization.
annotation.rimMapping: unique(./controlAct[classCode="CACT" and classCode="EVN" and isNormalAct()]/participation[typeCode="ENT" and isNormalParticipation]/role[classCode="ASSIGNED" and isNormalRole()]/player[isNormalEntity() and classCode=("DEV", "PSN") and determinerCode="INST"])
annotation.v2Mapping: EVN-5-operator ID / ORC-10-entered by / PRT-5-Participation Person:PRT-4-Participation='EP' / ROL where ROL.3 is EP or ORC.10

annotation.definition: The logical author of the message - the person or device that decided the described event should happen. Where there is more than one candidate, pick the most proximal to the MessageHeader. Can provide other authors in extensions.
annotation.comment: Usually only for the request, but can be used in a response.
annotation.requirements: Need to know for audit/traceback requirements and possibly for authorization.
annotation.rimMapping: unique(./controlAct[classCode="CACT" and classCode="EVN" and isNormalAct()]/participation[isHighest(priorityCode) and typeCode="AUT" and isNormalParticipation]/role[classCode="ASSIGNED" and isNormalRole()]/player[isNormalEntity() and classCode=("DEV", "PSN") and determinerCode="INST"])
annotation.v2Mapping: ORC-19-action by / PRT-5-Participation Person:PRT-4-Participation='AUT' / ROL where ROL.3 is IP or ORC.12

annotation.definition: Allows data conveyed by a message to be addressed to a particular person or department when routing to a specific application isn't sufficient.
annotation.requirements: Allows routing beyond just the application level.
annotation.rimMapping: Not directly supported. Could be shared using attentionLine.value with an appropriate keyWordText
annotation.committeeNotes: Is this in the 80%?

annotation.definition: The person or organization that accepts overall responsibility for the contents of the message. The implication is that the message event happened under the policies of the responsible party.
annotation.comment: Usually only for the request, but can be used in a response.
annotation.requirements: Need to know for audit/traceback requirements and possibly for authorization.
annotation.rimMapping: unique(./controlAct[classCode="CACT" and classCode="EVN" and isNormalAct()]/participation[isHighest(priorityCode) and typeCode="RESP" and isNormalParticipation]/role[classCode="ASSIGNED" and isNormalRole()]/player[isNormalEntity() and classCode="PSN" and determinerCode="INST"] or ./controlAct[classCode="CACT" and classCode="EVN" and isNormalAct()]/participation[isHighest(priorityCode) and typeCode="RESP" and isNormalParticipation]/role[classCode="ASSIGNED" and isNormalRole()]/scoper[isNormalEntity() and classCode="ORG" and determinerCode="INST"])
annotation.v2Mapping: ORC-12-ordering provider / PRT-5-Participation Person:PRT-4-Participation='OP' / PRT-8-Participation Organization:PRT-4-Participation='OP' / ROL where ROL.3 is RO or ORC.11

annotation.definition: Coded indication of the cause for the event - indicates a reason for the occurance of the event that is a focus of this message.
annotation.requirements: Need to be able to track why resources are being changed and report in the audit log/history of the resource. May affect authorization.
annotation.v2Mapping: EVN.4 / ORC.16 / OBR-31-reason for study / BPO-13-BP indication for use / RXO-20-indication / RXE-27-give indication / RXD-21-indication / RXG-22-indication / RXA-19-indication

annotation.shortDefinition: The actual content of the message
annotation.definition: The actual data of the message - a reference to the root/focus class of the event.
annotation.comment: The data is defined where the transaction type is defined. The transaction data is always included in the bundle that is the full message. Only the root resource is specified. The resources it references should be contained in the bundle but are not also listed here. Multiple repetitions are allowed to cater for merges and other situations with multiple focal targets.
annotation.requirements: Every message event is about actual data, a single resource, that is identified in the definition of the event, and perhaps some or all linked resources.
annotation.rimMapping: unique(./controlAct[classCode="CACT" and classCode="EVN" and isNormalAct()]/participation[typeCode="SUBJ" and isNormalParticipation]/role or ./controlAct[classCode="CACT" and classCode="EVN" and isNormalAct()]/outboundRelationship[typeCode="SBJ" and isNormalActRelatoinship]/target)

annotations.shortDefinition: System of unique identification
annotations.definition: A curated namespace that issues unique symbols within that namespace for the identification of concepts, people, devices, etc. Represents a "System" used within the Identifier and Coding data types.
A nested type in NamingSystem: Indicates how the system may be identified when referenced in electronic exchange.

annotation.definition: Identifies the unique identifier scheme used for this particular identifier.
annotation.comment: Different identifier types may be used in different types of communications (OIDs for v3, URIs for FHIR, etc.). Other includes RUIDs from v3, standard v2 code name strings, etc.

annotation.definition: The string that should be sent over the wire to identify the code system or identifier system.

annotation.shortDefinition: Is this the id that should be used for this type
annotation.definition: Indicates whether this identifier is the "preferred" identifier of this type.
Identifies the period of time over which this identifier is considered appropriate to refer to the namingsystem. Outside of this window, the identifier might be non-deterministic.
annotation.comment: Within a registry, a given identifier should only be "active" for a single namespace at a time. (Ideally, an identifier should only ever be associated with a single namespace across all time).

annotations.definition: A nested type in NamingSystem: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of a individual to contact
annotation.definition: The name of an individual to contact regarding the naming system.
annotation.comment: If there is no named individual, the telecom is for the organization as a whole.

annotation.shortDefinition: Contact details for individual or publisher
annotation.definition: Contact details for individual (if a name was provided) or the publisher.

binding.definition: Codes for identifying countries

binding.name: NamingSystemIdentifierType
binding.definition: Identifies the style of unique identifier used to identify a namepace

code.definition: A universally unique identifier of the form a5afddf4-e880-459b-876e-e4591b0acc11
A uniform resource identifier (ideally a URL - uniform resource locator). E.g. http://unitsofmeasure.org
Some other type of unique identifier. E.g HL7-assigned reserved string such as LN for LOINC

The namingsystem is used to manage identifiers (e.g. license numbers, order numbers, etc.)
The namingsystem is used as the root for other identifiers and namingsystems

binding.name: NamingSystemCategory
binding.definition: Identifies the general purpose of the namingsystem identifiers provided. E.g. Driver, Provider, Patient, Bank, etc.

annotation.definition: Indicates the purpose for the namingsystem - what kinds of things does it make unique?
The descriptive name of this particular identifier type or code system.
annotation.comment: The"symbolic name" for an OID would be captured as an extension.

annotation.definition: The date (and optionally time) when the system was registered or published.
Indicates whether the namingsystem is "ready for use" or not.

If present, indicates that the identifier or code system is principally intended for use or applies to entities within the specified country. For example, the country associated with a national code system.

annotation.shortDefinition: e.g. driver, provider, patient, bank etc
annotation.definition: Categorizes a namingsystem for easier search by grouping related namingsystems.
annotation.comment: This will most commonly be used for identifier namespaces, but categories could potentially be useful for code systems and authorities as well.

annotation.definition: The name of the organization that is responsible for issuing identifiers or codes for this namespace and ensuring their non-collision.
annotation.comment: This is the primary organization. Responsibility for some aspects of a namespace may be delegated.

annotation.definition: Details about what the namespace identifies including scope, granularity, version labeling, etc.
Provides guidance on the use of the namespace, including the handling of formatting characters, use of upper vs. lower case, etc.
Indicates how the system may be identified when referenced in electronic exchange.
annotation.comment: Multiple identifiers may exist, either due to duplicate registration, regional rules, needs of different communication technologies, etc.

annotation.shortDefinition: Name of the publisher (Organization or individual)
annotation.definition: The name of the individual or organization that published the naming system.
annotation.comment: Usually an organization, but may be an individual. This item SHOULD be populated unless the information is available from context.
annotation.requirements: Helps establish the "authority/credibility" of the naming system. May also allow for contact.

annotation.definition: Contacts to assist a user in finding and communicating with the publisher.
annotation.comment: May be a web site, an email address, a telephone number (tel:), etc.

annotation.definition: For namingsystems that are retired, indicates the namingsystem that should be used in their place (if any).

annotations.shortDefinition: A request for a diet, formula or nutritional supplement
annotations.definition: A request to supply a diet, formula feeding (enteral) or oral nutritional supplement to a patient/resident.
annotations.comment: Referenced by an Order Request (workflow).

annotations.definition: A nested type in NutritionOrder: Feeding provided through the gastrointestinal tract via a tube, catheter, or stoma that delivers nutrition distal to the oral cavity.

annotation.shortDefinition: Type of enteral or infant formula
annotation.definition: The type of enteral or infant formula such as an adult standard formula with fiber or a soy-based infant formula.

annotation.shortDefinition: Product or brand name of the enteral or infant formula
annotation.definition: The product or brand name of the enteral or infant formula product such as "ACME Adult Standard Formula".
annotation.committeeNotes: 2/4/2015 EH: [#4000][#4001][#4002] change ...name to ...productName.

annotation.shortDefinition: Type of modular component to add to the feeding
annotation.definition: Indicates the type of modular component such as protein, carbohydrate, fat or fiber to be provided in addition to or mixed with the base formula.
annotation.rimMapping: N/A (not differentiated from NutritionalFormulaType in V3)

annotation.shortDefinition: Product or brand name of the modular additive
annotation.definition: The product or brand name of the type of modular component to be added to the formula.
annotation.committeeNotes: 2/4/2015 EH: [#4000][#4001][#4002] change ...name to ...productName.

annotation.shortDefinition: Amount of energy per specified volume that is required
annotation.definition: The amount of energy (Calories) that the formula should provide per specified volume, typically per mL or fluid oz. For example, an infant may require a formula the provides 24 Calories per fluid ounce or an adult may require an enteral formula that provides 1.5 Calorie/mL.

annotation.shortDefinition: How the formula should enter the patient's gastrointestinal tract
annotation.definition: The route or physiological path of administration into the patient 's gastrointestinal tract for purposes of providing the formula feeding, e.g., nasogastric tube.

annotation.shortDefinition: Formula feeding instruction as structured data
annotation.definition: Formula administration instructions as structured data. This repeating structure allows for changing the administration rate or volume over time for both bolus and continuous feeding. An example of this would be an instruction to increase the rate of continuous feeding every 2 hours.
annotation.comment: See implementation notes below for further discussion on how to order continuous vs bolus enteral feeding using this resource.

annotation.shortDefinition: Upper limit on formula volume per unit of time
annotation.definition: The maximum total quantity of formula that may be administered to a subject over the period of time, e.g., 1440 mL over 24 hours.

annotation.shortDefinition: Formula feeding instructions expressed as text
annotation.definition: Free text formula administration, feeding instructions or additional instructions or information.
annotation.comment: Free text dosage instructions can be used for cases where the instructions are too complex to code.

annotations.definition: A nested type in NutritionOrder: Diet given orally in contrast to enteral (tube) feeding.

annotation.shortDefinition: Type of oral diet or diet restrictions that describe what can be consumed orally
annotation.definition: The kind of diet or dietary restriction such as fiber restricted diet or diabetic diet.
annotation.committeeNotes: renamed from .code to .type for consistency.

annotation.definition: The time period and frequency at which the diet should be given.
annotation.committeeNotes: 2/4/2015 EH: [#3996] Remove NutritionOrder.Item and push schedule/timing down into each type #8181.

annotation.definition: Class that defines the quantity and type of nutrient modifications required for the oral diet.
Class that describes any texture modifications required for the patient to safely consume various types of solid foods.

annotation.shortDefinition: The required consistency of fluids and liquids provided to the patient
annotation.definition: The required consistency (e.g., honey-thick, nectar-thick, thin, thickened.) of liquids or fluids served to the patient.

annotation.shortDefinition: Instructions or additional information about the oral diet
annotation.definition: Free text or additional instructions or information pertaining to the oral diet.
annotation.comment: Free text dosage instructions can be used for cases where the instructions are too complex to code.

annotations.definition: A nested type in NutritionOrder: Class that defines the quantity and type of nutrient modifications required for the oral diet.

annotation.shortDefinition: Type of nutrient that is being modified
annotation.definition: The nutrient that is being modified such as carbohydrate or sodium.
The quantity of the specified nutrient to include in diet.
annotation.committeeNotes: 2/4/2015 EH: [#4004] remove choice from .nutient.amount.

annotations.definition: A nested type in NutritionOrder: Formula administration instructions as structured data. This repeating structure allows for changing the administration rate or volume over time for both bolus and continuous feeding. An example of this would be an instruction to increase the rate of continuous feeding every 2 hours.

annotation.definition: The time period and frequency at which the enteral formula should be delivered to the patient.
annotation.committeeNotes: 2/4/2015 EH: [#3996] Remove NutritionOrder.Item and push schedule/timing down into each type, #6101,#6100, 6111.

annotation.shortDefinition: The volume of formula to provide
annotation.definition: The volume of formula to provide to the patient per the specified administration schedule.

annotation.shortDefinition: Speed with which the formula is provided per period of time
annotation.definition: The rate of administration of formula via a feeding pump, e.g., 60 mL per hour, according to the specified schedule.
annotation.comment: Ratio is used when the quantity value in the denominator is not "1", otherwise use Quantity. For example, the Ratio datatype is used for "200 mL/4 hrs" versus the Quantity datatype for "50 mL/hr".

annotations.definition: A nested type in NutritionOrder: Class that describes any texture modifications required for the patient to safely consume various types of solid foods.

annotation.shortDefinition: Code to indicate how to alter the texture of the foods, e.g., pureed
annotation.definition: Any texture modifications (for solid foods) that should be made, e.g. easy to chew, chopped, ground, and pureed.
annotation.comment: Coupled with the foodType (Meat).

annotation.shortDefinition: Concepts that are used to identify an entity that is ingested for nutritional purposes
annotation.definition: The food type(s) (e.g., meats, all foods) that the texture modification applies to. This could be all foods types.
annotation.comment: Coupled with the textureModifier; could be (All Foods).

annotations.definition: A nested type in NutritionOrder: Oral nutritional products given in order to add further nutritional value to the patient's diet.

annotation.definition: The kind of nutritional supplement product required such as a high protein or pediatric clear liquid supplement.

annotation.shortDefinition: Product or brand name of the nutritional supplement
annotation.definition: The product or brand name of the nutritional supplement such as "Acme Protein Shake".
annotation.committeeNotes: 2/4/2015 EH: [#4000][#4001][#4002] change ...name to ...productName.

annotation.definition: The time period and frequency at which the supplement(s) should be given.
annotation.committeeNotes: 2/4/2015 EH: [#3996] Remove NutritionOrder.Item and push schedule/timing down into each type. #8181.

annotation.definition: The amount of the nutritional supplement to be given.

annotation.shortDefinition: Instructions or additional information about the oral supplement
annotation.definition: Free text or additional instructions or information pertaining to the oral supplement.
annotation.comment: Free text dosage instructions can be used for cases where the instructions are too complex to code.

binding.definition: Codes used to indicate the type of food that should NOT be given to the patient.

binding.name: EnteralRouteOfAdministration
binding.definition: Codes specifying the route of administration of enteral formula.

binding.definition: Codes for type of enteral formula to be administered to patient.

binding.name: PatientDiet

binding.name: FluidConsistencyType
binding.definition: Codes used to represent the consistency of fluids and liquids provided to the patient.

binding.name: SupplementType

code.display: Adult high protein high fiber formula
Pediatric high energy formula with increased fiber
High energy enteral formula with fiber
Diabetic high calorie high protein enteral formula with fiber

binding.name: NutritionOrderStatus
binding.definition: Codes specifying the state of the request. Describes the lifecycle of the nutrition order.

code.definition: The request is in preliminary form prior to being sent
The request is 'actionable', but not all actions that are implied by it have occurred yet.
Actions implied by the request have been temporarily halted, but are expected to continue later. May also be called "suspended".
All actions that are implied by the order have occurred and no continuation is planned (this will rarely be made explicit).
The request has been withdrawn and is no longer actionable.

binding.name: OralDiet
binding.definition: Codes used to indicate the type of diet being ordered for a patient.

binding.name: NutrientModifier
binding.definition: Codes for types of nutrient that is being modified such as carbohydrate or sodium.

binding.name: EnteralFormulaAdditiveType
binding.definition: Codes for the type of modular component such as protein, carbohydrate or fiber to be provided in addition to or mixed with the base formula.

binding.name: TextureModifier
binding.definition: Codes for food consistency types or texture modifications to apply to foods.

annotation.shortDefinition: The person who requires the diet, formula or nutritional supplement
annotation.definition: The person (patient) who needs the nutrition order for an oral diet, nutritional supplement and/or enteral or formula feeding.
annotation.committeeNotes: 2/4/2015 EH: [#3707] change subject to patient.

annotation.shortDefinition: Who ordered the diet, formula or nutritional supplement
annotation.definition: The practitioner that holds legal responsibility for ordering the diet, nutritional supplement, or formula feedings.
Identifiers assigned to this order by the order sender or by the order receiver.

annotation.shortDefinition: The encounter associated with that this nutrition order
annotation.definition: An encounter that provides additional information about the healthcare context in which this request is made.

annotation.shortDefinition: Date and time the nutrition order was requested
annotation.definition: The date and time that this nutrition order was requested.

annotation.shortDefinition: proposed | draft | planned | requested | active | on-hold | completed | cancelled
annotation.definition: The workflow status of the nutrition order/request.
annotation.comment: Typically the system placing the order sets the status to requested. There after, the order is maintained by the receiver that updates the status as the request is handled.

annotation.shortDefinition: List of the patient's food and nutrition-related allergies and intolerances
annotation.definition: A link to a record of allergies or Intolerances which should be included in the nutrition order.
annotation.comment: Information on a patient's food allergies and intolerances, inform healthcare personnel about the type of foods that the patient should receive or consume.
annotation.committeeNotes: resource reference.

annotation.shortDefinition: Order-specific modifier about the type of food that should be given
annotation.definition: This modifier is used to convey order-specific modifiers about the type of food that should be given. These can be derived from patient allergies, intolerances, or preferences such as Halal, Vegan or Kosher. This modifier applies to the entire nutrition order inclusive of the oral diet, nutritional supplements and enteral formula feedings.
annotation.comment: Information on a patient's food preferences inform healthcare personnel about the food that the patient should receive or consume.
annotation.committeeNotes: Discussion at WGM Mon Q3 - maybe .foodPreferenceModifier --how to convey the patient No Soy, No Red Meat? (without a negation indicator) Do what domain expects e.g. ExcludeFoodType and IncludeFoodPreference.

annotation.shortDefinition: Order-specific modifier about the type of food that should not be given
annotation.definition: This modifier is used to convey order-specific modifiers about the type of food that should NOT be given. These can be derived from patient allergies, intolerances, or preferences such as No Red Meat, No Soy or No Wheat or Gluten-Free. This modifier applies to the entire nutrition order inclusive of the oral diet, nutritional supplements and enteral formula feedings.
annotation.comment: Information on a patient's food allergies and intolerances, and preferences inform healthcare personnel about the type of foods that the patient should receive or consume.
annotation.committeeNotes: Discussion at WGM Mon Q3 - maybe .foodPreferenceModifier --how to convey the patient No Soy, No Red Meat? (without a negation indicator) Do what domain expects e.g. ExcludeFoodType and IncludeFoodPreference.

annotation.definition: Diet given orally in contrast to enteral (tube) feeding.
Oral nutritional products given in order to add further nutritional value to the patient's diet.
Feeding provided through the gastrointestinal tract via a tube, catheter, or stoma that delivers nutrition distal to the oral cavity.

invariant.human: Nutrition Order SHALL contain either Oral Diet , Supplement, or Enteral Formula class

annotations.shortDefinition: Measurements and simple assertions
annotations.definition: Measurements and simple assertions made about a patient, device or other subject.
annotations.comment: Used for simple observations such as device measurements, laboratory atomic results, vital signs, height, weight, smoking status, comments, etc. Other resources are used to provide context for observations such as Lab reports, etc.
annotations.requirements: Observations are a key aspect of healthcare. This resource is used to capture those that do not require more sophisticated mechanisms.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Observation: Guidance on how to interpret the value by comparison to a normal or recommended range.

annotation.definition: The value of the low bound of the reference range. If this element is omitted, the low bound of the reference range is assumed to be meaningless. (e.g. reference range is <2.3) If the low.comparator element is missing, it is assumed to be '>'.

The value of the high bound of the reference range. If this element is omitted, the high bound of the reference range is assumed to be meaningless. (e.g. reference range is > 5) If the low.comparator element is missing , it is assumed to be '<'.

annotation.shortDefinition: Indicates the meaning/use of this range of this range
annotation.definition: Code for the meaning of the reference range.
annotation.comment: This SHOULD be populated if there is more than one range.
annotation.requirements: Need to be able to say what kind of reference range this is - normal, recommended, therapeutic, or perhaps what state this reference range applies to (i.e. age, hormonal cycles, etc.).

annotation.definition: The age at which this reference range is applicable. This is a neonatal age (e.g. number of weeks at term) if the meaning says so.
annotation.requirements: Some analytes vary greatly over age.

annotation.shortDefinition: Text based reference range in an observation
annotation.definition: Text based reference range in an observation which may be used when a quantitative range is not appropriate for an observation. An example would be a reference value of "Negative" or a list or table of 'normals'.

annotations.definition: A nested type in Observation: A reference to another resource ( usally another Observation but could also be a QuestionnaireAnswer) whose relationship is defined by the relationship type code.

annotation.shortDefinition: has-member | derived-from | sequel-to | replaces | qualified-by | interfered-by
annotation.definition: A code specifying the kind of relationship that exists with the target resource.
annotation.comment: "derived-from" is only logical choice when referencing QuestionnaireAnswer resource.
annotation.requirements: A relationship type SHOULD be provided.

annotation.shortDefinition: Resource that is related to this one
annotation.definition: A reference to the observation or questionnaireanswer that is related to this observation.
annotation.committeeNotes: can an invarient be made to limit code when referencing a resource type?

annotations.definition: A nested type in Observation: Some observations have multiple component observations. These component observations are expressed as separate code value pairs that share the same attributes. Examples include systolic and diastolic component observations for blood pressure measurement and multiple component observations for for genetics observations.

annotation.definition: Describes what was observed. Sometimes this is called the observation "code".
annotation.requirements: Knowing what kind of observation is being made is essential to understanding the observation.

annotation.definition: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.
annotation.comment: Normally, an observation will have either a value or a set of related observations. A few observations (e.g. apgar store) may have both a value and related observations (for an apgar score, the observations from which the measure is derived). If a value is present, the datatype for this element should be determined by Observation.code. A CodeableConcept with just a text would be used instead of a string if the field was usually coded, or if the type associated with the Observation.code defines a coded value. For boolean values use valueCodeableConcept and select codes from <http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/v2-0136> (These "yes/no" concepts can be mapped to the display name "true/false" or other mutually exclusive terms that may be needed"). The element, Observation.value[x], has a variable name depending on the type as follows: valueQuantity, valueCodeableConcept, valueRatio, valueChoice, valuePeriod, valueSampleData, or valueString (The name format is "'value' + the type name" with a capital on the first letter of the type).
annotation.requirements: An observation exists to have a value, though it may not if it is in error, or it represents a group of observations.

annotation.shortDefinition: Why the component result is missing
annotation.definition: Provides a reason why the expected value in the element Observation.value[x] is missing.
annotation.comment: "Null" or exceptional values can be represented two ways in FHIR Observations. One way is to simply include them in the value set and represent the exceptions in the value. For example, measurement values for a serology test could be "detected", "not detected", "inconclusive", or "test not done". The alternate way is to use the value element for actual observations and use the explicit dataAbsentReason element to record exceptional values. For example, the dataAbsentReason code "error" could be used when the measurement was not completed. Because of these options, use-case agreements are required to interpret general observations for exceptional values.
annotation.requirements: For many results it is necessary to handle exceptional values in measurements.

annotation.shortDefinition: Provides guide for interpretation ofcomponent result
annotation.definition: Guidance on how to interpret the value by comparison to a normal or recommended range.
annotation.comment: Most observations only have one generic reference range. Systems MAY choose to restrict to only supplying the relevant reference range based on knowledge about the patient (e.g. specific to the patient's age, gender, weight and other factors), but this may not be possible or appropriate. Whenever more than one reference range is supplied, the differences between them SHOULD be provided in the reference range and/or age properties.
annotation.requirements: Knowing what values are considered "normal" can help evaluate the significance of a particular result. Need to be able to provide multiple reference ranges for different contexts.

code.definition: The result has no reliability concerns
An early estimate of value; measurement is still occurring
An early estimate of value; processing is still occurring
The observation value should be treated with care
The result has been generated while calibration is occurring
The observation could not be completed because of an error

binding.definition: Codes specifying why the result (Observation.value[x]) is missing

code.definition: The source human does not know the value
There is reason to expect (from the workflow) that the value may become known
The workflow didn't lead to this value being known
The information is not available due to security, privacy or related reasons
The source system wasn't capable of supporting this element
The content of the data is represented in the resource narrative
Some system or workflow process error means that the information is not available

binding.name: ObservationValue
binding.definition: Codes identifying atomic results of observations when value is type codeableConcept

binding.name: ObservationRelationshipType
binding.definition: Codes specifying how two observations are related

code.definition: This observation is a group observation (e.g. a battery, a panel of tests, a set of vital sign measurements) that includes the target as a member of the group

The target resource (Observation or QuestionnaireAnswer) is part of the information from which this observation value is derived. (e.g. calculated anion gap, Apgar score) NOTE: "derived-from" is only logical choice when referencing QuestionnaireAnswer
This observation follows the target observation (e.g. timed tests such as Glucose Tolerance Test)
This observation replaces a previous observation (i.e. a revised value). The target observation is now obsolete
The value of the target observation qualifies (refines) the semantics of the source observation (e.g. a lipaemia measure target from a plasma measure)

The value of the target observation interferes (degardes quality, or prevents valid observation) with the semantics of the source observation (e.g. a hemolysis measure target from a plasma potassium measure which has no value)

binding.name: ObservationStatus
binding.definition: Codes providing the status of an observation

code.definition: The existence of the observation is registered, but there is no result yet available
This is an initial or interim observation: data may be incomplete or unverified
The observation is complete and verified by an authorized person
The observation has been modified subsequent to being Final, and is complete and verified by an authorized person
The observation is unavailable because the measurement was not started or not completed (also sometimes called "aborted")
The observation has been withdrawn following previous Final release
The observation status is unknown. Note that "unknown" is a value of last resort and every attempt should be made to provide a meaningful value other than "unknown"

annotation.definition: The assessment made based on the result of the observation.

annotation.definition: May include statements about significant, unexpected or unreliable values, or information about the source of the value where this may be relevant to the interpretation of the result.

annotation.v2Mapping: NTE.3 (partner NTE to OBX, or sometimes another (child?) OBX)

annotation.definition: The time or time-period the observed value is asserted as being true. For biological subjects - e.g. human patients - this is usually called the "physiologically relevant time". This is usually either the time of the procedure or of specimen collection, but very often the source of the date/time is not known, only the date/time itself.
annotation.comment: At least a date should be present unless this observation is a historical report.
annotation.requirements: Knowing when an observation was deemed true is important to its relevance as well as determining trends.
annotation.v2Mapping: OBX-14-date/time of the observation, and/or OBX-19 after v2.4 (depends on who observation made)

annotation.definition: The date and time this observation was made available.
annotation.comment: Updated when the result is updated.
annotation.v2Mapping: OBR.22 (or MSH.7), or perhaps OBX-19 (depends on who observation made)

annotation.definition: The status of the result value.
annotation.requirements: Need to track the status of individual results - some results are finalised before the whole report is finalised.

status

annotation.shortDefinition: ok | ongoing | early | questionable | calibrating | error +
annotation.definition: An estimate of the degree to which quality issues have impacted on the value reported.
annotation.comment: Note that in most contexts, unreliable results are not recorded, deleted, or otherwise excluded, but it's not always possible to exclude them from the record. If the reliability indicator is present, interpreters of a result, whether human or machine, should always either be aware of the status or prevented from using the observation without being unaware that the reliability is not "ok".
annotation.requirements: Not all results are completely reliable, and some are still reported anyway.

annotation.definition: Indicates the site on the subject's body where the observation was made ( i.e. the target site).
annotation.comment: Only used if not implicit in code found in Observation.code.
